<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Fire Destroys Seven Oil Tanks in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A big fire which broke out in
Assam State of eastern India on Tuesday, destroyed seven oil tanks
of the Indian Oil Corporation, official sources said here Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Ten fire tenders are still fighting to extinguish the blaze,
with its spread now under control.
</P>
<P>
The fire was first spotted by a security guard Tuesday morning
in an oil tank which was followed by a loud explosion. The blaze
soon engulfed the other tanks -- three containing kerosene oil and
two each of gasoline and diesel.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the fire is yet to be known. One senior police
officer, who visited the site, has ruled out involvement of
militants as reported earlier. He said the fire could have been
caused by an electric short circuit. Some sources, however, have
asserted that it could be a case of internal sabotage.
</P>
<P>
The explosion was followed by black rain containing carbon and
other solid particles. It is being investigated to ascertain its
links with the tank fire, the same sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
