<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bankruptcy Applications Continue at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Increased Americans applied
for federal bankruptcy protection in the 12 months that ended on
June 30, more than any one-year period in history, the
Administrative Office of the U.S. courts reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Federal bankruptcy filings climbed to a record high 1.42
million for those 12 months, due largely to a 9.2 percent increase
in personal bankruptcies, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that the number of business bankruptcies dropped
from the 53,993 filed in the 12-month period ending in June 1997
to 50,202. But nonbusiness or personal bankruptcies were up from
1.26 million to 1.37 million.
</P>
<P>
In February, the office reported that 1.4 million bankruptcy
petitions were filed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The most common form of bankruptcy proceeding is filed under
the federal code's Chapter 7, designed to allow individuals to
keep certain belongings while selling off other property to repay
creditors. Businesses that file under Chapter 7 sell off all
assets and are being forced to cease doing business.
</P>
<P>
For the 12 months ending last June 30, 1.01 million Chapter 7
petitions were filed.
</P>
<P>
More than 400,000 petitions were filed under the code's Chapter
13, which allows debtors to repay creditors in installments, in
full or in part, over a period of years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
