<HEADLINE> India Develops Longer Range Version of Missile Agni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- India has started developing a
longer range version of intermediate range ballistic missile Agni,
Defense Minister George Fernandes said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a briefing to the consultative committee of members of the
parliament attached to the Defense Ministry, Fernandes said the
government's recent approval of the second phase of missile Agni
followed the successful completion of the first phase
demonstrating re-entry technology.
</P>
<P>
India has so far flight-tested thrice the Agni missile with a
range of 1,500 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The new version of the missile would have a strike range much
longer than its present 1,500 kilometers. The new range is
expected to reach 2,500 kilometers or more.
</P>
<P>
The Agni missile is part of India's integrated guided missile
program spearheaded by the Defense Research and Development
Organization in the 1980s, which also included surface-to-surface
missile Prithvi, surface-to-air missile Trishul, surface-to-air
missile Akash and anti-tank missile Nag.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister told the committee that efforts are on to
ensure that the sanctions imposed by the United States following
the country's five nuclear tests in mid-May this year will have no
adverse effects on the missile program which is in a very advanced
stage of development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
