<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Productivity Dips in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua)-- The U.S. workers' productivity
declined during the second quarter of the year for the first time
in more than three years, the Labor Department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Productivity of nonfarm, nonsupervisory workers, output per
hour of work, dropped at a 0.2 percent annual rate, according to
the department.
</P>
<P>
The second-quarter productivity decrease was the first since a
drop at a 0.4 percent rate during the first three months of 1995.
However, it followed an increase at a 3.5 percent rate in the
first quarter, the strongest in two years.
</P>
<P>
The decline is attributed to the fact that most employers kept
their payrolls at full strength despite a sharp slowing in
economic output caused by the falling export to Asia, the General
Motors strike and the need to sell goods that had piled up in
inventory.
</P>
<P>
However, with labor scarce, particularly for skilled jobs,
employers have been reluctant to order layoffs for fear they'd
have trouble getting workers back when they needed them.
</P>
<P>
As a result, unit labor costs, a key measure of inflation
pressure, increased at a 4.1 percent rate in the second quarter,
the highest in four years, after growing at a modest 1.1 percent
rate in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Productivity, after growing at a brisk 2.9 percent annual rate
in the 1960s and early 1970s, slowed to only a 1 percent from 1974
through 1995. It climbed to a 2.4 percent rate in 1996 and
maintained a 1.4 percent rate through 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
