<HEADLINE> World Oil Prices Dive to 10-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The world's sluggish oil markets
Tuesday slumped to 10-year lows with global benchmark Brent crude
oil sinking to 11.55 U.S. dollars on the London futures market.
</P>
<P>
Although prices later recovered some ground to 11.76 dollars a
barrel around 1500 GMT, oil has already lost a dollar a barrel in
two days as concern grows about the size of a mountainous glut of
crude and petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the price slide is expected to pressure
share prices of major oil companies and deliver a severe blow to
non-OPEC Russia.
</P>
<P>
They say Russian producers must now cut output and close wells
producing at a loss or undertake serious cost-cutting to weather
the current world oil price crisis.
</P>
<P>
London brokers GNI said that neither renewed confrontation
between the United Nations and Iraq nor bombings of U.S. embassies
in Africa were likely to support the sickly oil market.
</P>
<P>
"The reality is that neither of these two issues is likely to
seriously interrupt the world supply of oil in the near term," the
GNI Energy Report was quoted by Reuters as saying.
</P>
<P>
GNI and other analysts say relief for prices could come only
from strict compliance with OPEC output cuts and a very cold
northern hemisphere winter which would hike heating oil demand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
