<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Urges Prime Minister Appointment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagabandy has called on the Great Hural, Mongolia's parliament, to
appoint a new prime minister, in face of a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came in a letter sent to Radnaasumberel Gonchigdory,
the chairman of the Great Hural Bagabandy, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hural dismissed Prime Minister Tsakhya Elbegdorj's
government last month.
</P>
<P>
This government's decision in May to merge the state-owned
Renovation Bank with the private Golomt Bank not only, it was
claimed, violated the country's constitution and laws but also
brought a threat to the national economic security and financial
policies.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of oil products and soaring oil prices led to a
continuing fall in Mongolia's currency, worsening the economic
situation and dampening the confidence of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
According to law, the Great Hural should appoint a new prime
minister within 30 days of the cabinet dismissal.
</P>
<P>
But until now, the parliamentary group formed by the Social
Democratic Party and the National Democratic party had not
discussed the problem with him, the president said.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian Democratic Party Committee last month nominated
Davaadorj Ganbold, vice-president of the party, as the candidate
of new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The nomination was approved by the Social Democratic party on
August 6.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolia's laws, the ruling party's parliamentary group
should discuss the nominees for prime minister with the president,
and the president then submits the nomination to the Great Hural
for approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
