<HEADLINE> NATO Plannings Concentrate More on Air Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker
Ruehe said Tuesday that military plannings by the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) for a possible intervention in Kosovo
are concentrating more on an air force operation in the Serbian
province.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the German ZDF television
network, Ruehe said that NATO ground forces could only be involved
if a peace accord had been reached in Kosovo and if all
conflicting parties had asked for such a deployment.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that legal conditions must also be created
even for an air operation.
</P>
<P>
According to German media reports, ambassadors of NATO
countries are due to meet in Brussels Wednesday to approve the
first plans for a possible NATO military operation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Options raised by NATO members so far ranged from air strikes
on Serbian military targets, separating Kosovo conflicting parties
through NATO forces, to a large-scale deployment of over 50,000
NATO ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, any such operations must need a U.N. mandate, NATO
officials said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, German government sources said
Tuesday that Bonn would agree to deploy up to 14 Tornado fighter
jets of the German air force for a possible NATO air operation in
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
