<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Purchases Amoco for 48 Bln Dlrs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The British Petroleum PLC
announced Tuesday that it would buy the Amoco Corp., the
fifth-largest U.S. oil company, for 48 billion U.S. dollars in
stock.
</P>
<P>
The deal could become the largest industrial merger in history.
The combined company will be called BP Amoco PLC, but in the
United States, BP gasoline stations would be renamed Amoco,
according to an AP report.
</P>
<P>
The deal surpasses the 36 billion dollar purchase of Chrysler
Corp. by Germany's Daimler Benz announced in May. Overall, the
deal ranks fifth, behind some big transactions in banking and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Amoco is already the biggest producer of natural gas in North
America, and combined with British Petroleum's production in
Alaska the company would be the biggest producer of oil and gas in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
BP is already the world's third largest oil company and the
deal will make it a bigger rival to No.1 Royal Dutch/Shell and
No.2 Exxon Corp.
</P>
<P>
Based on last year's figure, the new BP Amoco would have annual
revenues of 108 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BP chief executive Sir John Browne will head the new group. Its
board will be co-chaired by BP chairman Peter Sutherland and Amoco
chairman Larry Fuller.
</P>
<P>
Amoco's office in Chicago will be headquarters for the group's
North American refining, marketing and transportation business and
its worldwide chemicals business.
</P>
<P>
The BP Amoco group will have combined oil and gas reserves
equivalent to about 14.8 billion barrels, and daily production of
some 3 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
The companies said cost savings from the deal would add 2
billion dollars to annual profits by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Amoco last year sold about one-third of its domestic oil
and natural gas properties. For the first six months of this year,
Amoco's profits fell nearly by half to 673 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
