<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Confident in Ugandan Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) is
satisfied with the overall management of its loans and grant to
the Ugandan government and will continue to increase its loans to
the country as the economy goes stronger, an official with WB
told Xinhua here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Robert Blake, a senior economist with Ugandan Resident Mission
of the WB, said the Ugandan government has been using the fund on
the spending priorities that the international financial
institution agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the influence of corruption in the Ugandan
government on WB's lending policy to the east African country,
Robert said:" The government has the political will to address
and solve the issue."
</P>
<P>
As for WB fund supplied to Uganda, it goes in grant, project
loans or adjustment loans, with the last being used for
government policy actions, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the WB provides some 250 to 280 million U.S.
Dollars to Uganda in each fiscal year, two times the figure for
the 1996-97 fiscal year and five times more than that for the
1995-96 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the loans are interest-free credits with 35-40 year
maturities, or the so called International Development
Association (IDA) loans while in few cases the credits are at
commercial interest, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year, the WB gave Uganda a grant of 75
million Dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
The WB-funded projects cover such key sectors as agriculture,
environment, livestock services, infrastruction construction,
water supply, power generation, AIDS prevention and so on. There
are nine upcoming WB-funded projects in Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
