<HEADLINE> France Sends 18 Mln Dlr Aid to Sudan's Famine Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- France has sent 18 million U.S.
dollars of humanitarian aid to Sudan's famine-stricken civilians
so far this year, said French Delegate Minister in charge of
cooperation with Africa Charles Josselin Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that Josselin visited Khartoum
from Monday evening until Tuesday and would meet with the leader
of the Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) John Garang in
Cairo on his way home late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with the leaders of the Sudanese organizations
for aiding southern Sudan and U.N. humanitarian aid agencies, such
as the World Food Program, in the Sudanese capital.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Sudanese officials focused on the famine
situation in Sudan and the peace efforts in southern Sudan to put
an end to the 15-year-old war between government forces and the
SPLA.
</P>
<P>
"We all know that there exists a direct link between the famine
and the civil war in the region," AFP quoted Josselin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government and the SPLA signed a cease-fire
agreement on July 15 to stop fighting in the southern Bahr
al-Ghazal region, because of the severe famine striking the local
population. 
</P>
