<HEADLINE> SADC Meeting to Discuss TB Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will this week host a
two-day Southern Africa TB Control Initiative (SATCI) to explore
ways of fighting the tuberculosis epidemic in the region.
</P>
<P>
The third annual general meeting of SATCI to be held in Harare
Thursday and Friday will be attended by delegates from 11
Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries.
</P>
<P>
"The SATCI meeting takes place at a time when the World Health
Organisation (WHO) has a bleak picture of the global failure of
the health systems to deal with the burden of tuberculosis," a
statement issued Tuesday by the Zimbabwean Health Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"However, in all SATCI countries, the Directly Observed
Treatment Shortcourse (DOTS) strategy has now been adapted and
either fully implemented or is in the process of being
implemented," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting expects to analyze existing budget monitoring
mechanisms pertaining to the control of TB in the SADC region.
</P>
<P>
The SATCI is an initiative aiming at a cooperative fight
against TB in the SADC region.
</P>
<P>
It seeks to promote a strong foundation for effective
tuberculosis control among SADC member states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
