<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Agrees to Negotiations on U.N. Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Tuesday that Israel would not object to
negotiations on formulating an international treaty to ban the
production of the fissionable material used to make unclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
But Israel Radio quoted the prime minister as telling the
cabinet that this attitude did not mean automatic Israeli support
for the final treaty. Israel still had principled objections which
it would try to clear up with the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli representatives to the United Nations Conference on
Disarmament in Geneva was to officially announce Israel's
decision later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 61-member organization, which takes decisions by consensus
with each member having veto rights, has been awaiting words from
Israel as to whether it would agree to launch fresh negotiations
aimed at halting production of nuclear bomb-making material.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. nuclear disarmament body has tried since 1995 to
revive the stalled talks on banning production of plutonium and
highly enriched uranium. And Israel has been the only member to
oppose the talks since India and Pakistan came to board after
massive pressure in the wake of their nuclear tests last May,
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the cabinet that U.S. President Bill Clinton had
requested Israel not to object to the formation of an ad hoc
committee which would start formulating the so-called "cut-off"
treaty.
</P>
<P>
To reassure those who raised their eyebrows, Netanyahu said
the formation of the committee was a "procedural process" and it
would take years before all countries participating could reach a
formulated and agreed-upon treaty.
</P>
<P>
Israel has made it clear that its support for the
establishment of the committee did not indicate it would
automatically support the final treaty, Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Worried about the possible impact of such a treaty on its
policy of "nuclear ambiguity," Israel is demanding that the
U.S. give it firm guarantees that international inspectors are not
sent to inspect its nuclear activity as may be stipulated in the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Israel's "don't ask, don't tell" nuclear policy, which aims to
keep others in dark over its true nuclear capability, has served
as a deterrence against potential attacks from hostile countries
in the region.
</P>
<P>
As a nuclear "threshold" state, Israel joined the Geneva
conference in June 1996 under a package which brought in 23
countries, including Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0027 </DOCNO>
