<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Utilization Gains New Impetus in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Government of Nigeria
has recently encouraged business sector to exploit abundant
natural gas in the country for export and domestic use.
</P>
<P>
Nine oil and gas companies operating in the country last week
formed a national body Nigerian Gas Association (NGA) to
encourage the increased utilization of natural gas resources.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the association said that it would work
towards an enabling environment with the government for the
industry and encourage industry safety and environmental
standards.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that "as we move into the 21st century,
gas will increase in importance as a source of energy and
industrial feedstocks in Nigeria and as a source of export
earnings."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a consultancy agreement for the feasibility study
on the West African Gas Pipeline project was signed last week
with a view to entailing technical and commercial analysis of the
conditions required to implement the project.
</P>
<P>
The project was designed to meet the energy requirements of
the West African region through the transmission of natural gas
from Nigeria to Benin, Togo and Ghana for power generation and
other uses.
</P>
<P>
The West African country of Nigeria has an abundant natural
gas reserve which was estimated at more than 3,500 billion cubic
feet.
</P>
<P>
Available data shows that about 2.5 billion cubic feet of
associated gas is produced daily by oil companies operating in
the country, but only 30 percent of the volume is utilized
locally while the remaining 70 percent has been flared for the
past four decades.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the Federal Government of Nigeria had
incurred about two billion U.S. Dollars loss in revenue annually
as a result of the continued flaring of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
With the increasing awareness of environmental protection, gas
flaring has become unacceptable both to the government and to
those who reside around the flaring sites.
</P>
<P>
It is against this background that the Federal Government of
Nigeria has drawn some laws which are aimed at ending gas flaring
and promulgated regulations providing stiffer penalty for gas
flaring.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Nigerian government has introduced a
series of generous incentives for the use of natural gas in the
country, including duty- and VAT-free import of related machinery
and equipment, a five-year tax exemption period, zero percent
royalty and zero percent petroleum profit tax for gas used.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent response to the government moves, oil companies
operating in the country have now set targets for the elimination
of gas flaring and all indications show that the country may get
close to zero gas flaring by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Government of Nigeria has also invested billions
of Dollars in the Nigeria Liquefied Natural Gas Ltd. in order to
produce more liquefied gas for export.
</P>
<P>
All the major oil companies in the country have embarked on
projects to use gas associated with oil production with the
biggest project under construction at a cost of 3.8 billion U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that all these moves taken by the Nigerian
government and oil companies are prompted by the need to end gas
flaring in the country, conserve the natural resources and
protect the country's environment.
</P>
<P>
Globally, there is an increase in natural gas consumption with
an average annual growth rate of about 2.5 percent because of low
carbon and sulphur emissions, cost efficiency and greater
efficiency in combined cycle power plants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-11 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Iran Agree to Enhance Ties: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Iran have reached "good
understanding" on enhancing their ties in various fields,
Jordanian Foreign Minister Jawad Anani said here upon return from
a three-day visit to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Anani said that he delivered on Sunday a message from King
Hussein of Jordan to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on
bilateral relations as well as other regional and international
issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
In the message, the king emphasized Jordan's keenness to
develop relations with Jordan in all fields and laid emphasis on
Jordan's concern over the image of Muslims and the need for
safeguarding Muslims' common interests, said Anani.
</P>
<P>
The king also invited Khatami to visit Jordan soon, and the
latter accepted the offer.
</P>
<P>
Anani said that during his stay in Tehran last week, he also
held talks with a number of other senior Iranian officials on ways
of boosting bilateral relations in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He said that he on Monday discussed with his Iranian
counterpart Kamal Kharazi the Arab-Iranian relations, especially
the obstacles blocking the progress in the Jordanian-Iranian ties
and the necessity to find solutions to them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anani said that he also reached consensus with
Iranian officials that the Judaization of the Arab East Jerusalem
by Israel should be rejected.
</P>
<P>
Both sides thought that the Israeli measures in the Holy City
were illegal, unacceptable and unjustified, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tehran severed its diplomatic ties with Amman during the
1980-88 Iraqi-Iranian war because of Jordan' support to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic ties were resumed in 1991, but have been
strained since 1995 when Jordan expelled an Iranian diplomat,
accusing him of performing acts incompatible with his status.
</P>
<P>
After the moderate Khatami was elected Iranian President last
year, the door was opened for better relations between Iran and
other states including Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Last November, Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan visited Iran to
attend meetings of the Organization of Islamic Conference, during
which he met Khatami and other senior officials to explore ways of
enhancing bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
