<HEADLINE> Arafat Praises Mandela's Role in Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat said Tuesday that he envisaged a particular
role for President Nelson Mandela in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Mandela and his deputy Thabo Mbeki
in Cape Town, Arafat told reporters that he had a 20-minute talk
with Mandela focussing on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We spoke frankly about that," Arafat said, but declined to
expand on what Mandela's envisaged role entailed.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his talks with Inkatha Freedom Party leader
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, Arafat said Palestine needed South Africa's
help "so that we can save this peace process".
</P>
<P>
Earlier, at a customary welcoming ceremony for visiting heads
of state, Mandela awarded Arafat South Africa's highest honor for
foreigners, the Order of Good Hope.
</P>
<P>
The award was in recognition of Arafat's contribution during
the struggle against apartheid and his commitment to a democratic
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Arafat in turn invested Mandela with Palestine's highest
decoration, the Star of Holy Jerusalem, for what he said was the
South African president's continued support for the just cause of an
independent Palestinian state, with Jerusalem as capital.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Arafat also witnessed the signing of two bilateral
declarations of intent on health and education by Palestinian
Minister of Local Government Sa'eb Erakat, and South African
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo.
</P>
<P>
Arafat Tuesday also met leaders of other opposition parties,
including National Party leader Marthinus van Schalkwyk and Pan
Africanist Congress leader Stanley Mogoba.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said Mandela would host a banquet Tuesday
night at his residence in honor of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cape Town last night for a three-day state
visit, which, officials of the two sides said, was designed to
reinforce relations between Palestine and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is due to return to South Africa at the end of the
month for a Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) Summit meeting, during
which South Africa will assume the Chair of the NAM.
</P>
<P>
The 113-nation NAM has historically been a strong supporter of
the Palestinians. 
</P>
