<HEADLINE> Annan Expresses Concern Over Developments in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday expressed his deep concern over the latest
developments in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
An uprising by troops broke out on August 2 in the eastern part
of the country which seems on the trend of escalation. Kabila's
government has accused Rwanda and Uganda of playing part by
helping the rebels.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the secretary-general said he was disturbed at
reported violations of the territorial integrity of the country
and about acts of intimidation ans violence against humanitarian
workers and other international personnel. Annan said he was also
deeply concerned about instances of ethnically-motivated
persecution.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his call to all parties to respect the human
rights and dignity of all civilians regardless of their origin, to
uphold the standards and principles of international humanitarian
law, to ensure the safety of U.N. personnel and all humanitarian
workers operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief welcomed the four-nation fact-finding mission to
the country and the dispatch of a mediation team from the
Organization of African Union to the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Annan hoped that these initiatives would encourage the parties
concerned to settle their differences peacefully. 
</P>
