<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Abates in Cyprus, Leaving 56 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- After nine consecutive days
of scorching heat, the worst heat wave in decades abated Tuesday
in Cyprus leaving 56 dead, most of whom are elderly people.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's temperatures fell to 39 degrees Celsius in Nicosia, 4
degrees lower than Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The small tragedy Cyprus went through in the past few days is
coming to an end, with the heat wave easing and temperatures going
back to normal levels," Health Minister Christos Solomis told
reporters after a visit to Larnaca General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that 56 people died of the heat wave over the
past week, most of them are elderly people with ill health.
</P>
<P>
Solomis lauded the work done by the hospitals' staff who were
on full alert to handle the increasing number of people admitted
to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over 3,500 people sought medical care
over the week with heat-related problems.
</P>
<P>
Acting President and Speaker of House of Representatives
Spyros Kyprianou praised the medical personnel for their
dedication, noting that many doctors and nurses who were on leave
voluntarily offered to return to work.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Department said that temperatures are
expected to fall to the monthly average of 37 degrees Celsius by
Thursday. But on Friday a slight increase is expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
