<HEADLINE> Lebanon Suggests Embassy Official Exchange With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 11 (Xinhua) -- In what regarded as a show of
intention towards the normalization of ties with Iraq, Lebanon
Tuesday suggested the two countries send officials to their
respective closed embassies in the other.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz,
Iraqi Ambassador to Jordan Nouri Ismail told reporters here that
Lebanon wants to appoint an administrative officer in its closed
embassy in Baghdad, the state-run National News agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It also hopes that Iraq do the same in order to handle
commercial services between the two countries, the ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral ties were severed following an assassination of
the Iraqi opposition figure Taleb Suhail al-Tamimi in Beirut in
1994.
</P>
<P>
Three Iraqi diplomats in Lebanon were convicted of killing
Tamimi and were arrested. One of them died in prison from a brain
haemorrhage and the others were later expelled.
</P>
<P>
Ismail also delivered a message from Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf to Boueiz which covered the bilateral
ties and ways of improving it.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts regarded the move as a significant step toward
restoring diplomatic relations as the business exchange between
the two countries is growing.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has gained a 50-million-U.S. dollar contract under the
Iraqi oil-for-food deal with the United Nations and is intending
to increase the amount to 100 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
