<HEADLINE> Iraq Rebuts U.N. Spokesman's Comment on Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Tuesday rebutted the
U.N. spokesman's statement that the U.N. Sanctions Committee did
not obstruct the approval of contracts that Iraq signed to buy
medicine and medical appliances.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as
saying that U.N. spokesman Jone Miles' denial of any obstruction
on Monday did not reflect the truth.
</P>
<P>
He said that regarding the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program, the
U.S and British representatives in the Sanctions Committee did
obstruct, and are still obstructing the approval of these
contracts.
</P>
<P>
He said since the Iraq-U.N. memorandum of understanding on the
oil-for-food program came into force in December 1996, the
U.S. and British representatives have been trying to create
pretexts to hamper the implementation of it.
</P>
<P>
Because of the U.S. and British obstruction, in the first
phase of the oil-for-food deal, only 80 percent of the contracted
medicine and medical appliances arrived in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, the proportion reduced to 50 percent, and
in the third phase, it further dropped to 0.5 percent, the
Iraqi spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The fourth phase of the oil-for-food program started on June 3
this year, but so far, none of the contracted medicine and
medical appliances have reached Iraq, he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also charged the U.S. and British
representatives for blocking the implementation of many other
contracts such as those on Iraq's purchase of the badly needed
spare parts for its oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the fourth phase of the oil-for-food deal, Iraq is
allowed to export 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil to
buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its
suffering people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has imposed comprehensive sanctions on Iraq after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
