<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Leaders Hold Talks in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt Tuesday hosted a meeting of
opposition leaders in northern and southern Sudan on how to end
the 15-year civil war in its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The meeting groups John Garang, leader of the Sudanese People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), Al-Sadeq Al-Mahdi, former Sudanese Prime
Minister and leader of the Ummah Party, and Mohammed Osman
Al-Merghani, the head of the National Democratic Alliance, the
umbrella group for northern and southern Sudanese oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister Youssef Wali represented Egypt
at the meeting, said Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, through its efforts to reconcile the conflicting
parties, is trying to close up ranks and preserve Sudan's unity,
diplomatic sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA, Sudan's largest rebel group, has been fighting for
autonomy of the largely Christian south from the Islamist north
since 1983. The civil war, combined with perennial famines, has
claimed more than 1.5 million lives in this North African country.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's meeting came after the peace talks between the
Sudanese government and the oppositions in the Ethiopian capital
of Addis Ababa ended Friday without any progress.
</P>
<P>
After four days of talks, differences remained over issues
including the cease-fire, border demarcation of southern Sudan,
the relationship between religion and state, and the referendum on
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa is to meet with Garang on
Wednesday to discuss Egypt's efforts to close the gap between
Khartoum and the oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Egypt have long been at odds over a border dispute
and have traded accusations of harboring rebel militants and
oppositions, but a tentative thaw in relations has been emerging
between the two sides in recent months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
