<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Taliban's Claim over Captured Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Tuesday rejected the
claim by the Afghan Taliban militia that it did not know the
whereabouts of 11 Iranian diplomats allegedly captured by it in
northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Tehran radio, Iran's special envoy on
Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi termed the Taliban's claim as
a violation of the international laws and principles.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Iranian diplomats, now held by Taliban in
Qandahar, were sound and the Taliban can not shirk responsibility
for their safety.
</P>
<P>
The "Foreign Ministry" of Taliban regime issued a statement
earlier Tuesday saying that it did not know the whereabouts of the
11 missing Iranians. It added that if it had arrested them, they
would be tried and punished as agents of a hostile government.
</P>
<P>
Iran believed that the 11 Iranian diplomats and a
correspondent of the Iranian official news agency IRNA were taken
captive by the Taliban fighters on Saturday after they took over
Mazari Sharif, northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians, who worked at the Iranian consulate in Mazari
Sharif, were reportedly late transferred to Qandahar, the Taliban's
headquarters in southern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said all the staff members of the Iranian consulate
in Mazari Sharif were sent by the Iranian government and were
recognized as diplomats according to international laws.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope the issue would be solved through efforts
by the Pakistani government in the near future. Shortly after the
capture of the Iranian diplomats, Iran has contacted Islamabad to
seek Pakistan's help in securing the release of them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boroujerdi confirmed that the Taliban militia also
arrested 31 Iranian drivers who transported goods to Afghanistan
and other central Asian republics.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban accused the Iranians of arming their enemies in
Mazari Sharif. Boroujerdi said that the arrest of the Iranian
drivers were against the humanitarian principles.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran has asked the International Committee of the
Red Cross to help secure the release of the Iranian nationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
