<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elephants in Tanzania's Second Largest National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Elephant population in
the Ruaha National Park, the second largest in Tanzania, has
increased significantly thanks to stern measures against poaching
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Wildlife experts said Tuesday in Dar es Salaam that the
elephant population which shrank by half because of poaching in
the 1980s, has risen to 22,000 in the park and the adjacent game
reserve.
</P>
<P>
"The figure may be higher as the elephant family groups with
many young calves are frequently seen unlike in the past," the
principal park warden, Mtango Mtahiko, said at the park
headquarters in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Great Ruaha ecosystem, covering 10,000 square kilometers
in southern region of Iringa, has about 32,000 elephants in early
1970s but had been reduced by half by 1990.
</P>
<P>
According to Mtahiko, the present estimation is based on an
animal census carried out inside the 34-year-old park during 1993
and 1994.
</P>
<P>
Ruaha, second only to the Serengeti National Park in size,
currently takes lead in elephant population among the 12 national
parks in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Despite the tight security measures, elephants were still
killed in isolated cases by poachers who coveted after their
tusks in the park and adjacent areas.
</P>
<P>
Interestingly, in the 1970s there was great concern that large
number of elephants were destroying trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
