<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Yemen Demarcating Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Yemen are
continuing their work to demarcate borders between them on
Tuesday, in an effort to prevent further border-related clashes.
</P>
<P>
The joint Saudi-Yemeni military committee's meeting on the
issue finished their second day in the Saudi port city Jeddah
Tuesday with both sides showing willingness for a quick and final
agreement, the Kuwait News Agency quoted Arab diplomatic sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors on the Arabian peninsula share a
2,000-kilometer common border and have a decades-long dispute over
three Red Sea islands and parts of the desert region, where huge
oil reserves are expected.
</P>
<P>
The border dispute between the two countries often flared into
armed confrontation. The latest clashes on July 19 on the Dowaima
island in the Red Sea left three Yemeni soldiers dead.
</P>
<P>
A joint commission authorized to tackle border clashes reached
an agreement last week to maintain the status quo of Dowaima.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi-Yemeni committee was established in 1995, charged
with the mission of border demarcation. It is scheduled to meet
again on August 29 to put forward operational measures aimed at
preventing further clashes. 
</P>
