<P>
ANKARA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Istanbul Stock Exchange
plunged 7.35 percent in active trading Tuesday to 3,432.48 points,
amid concerns over the worsening Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government's possible sharp devaluation of the
Turkish lira against Western currencies has also prompted
investors to sell shares on the market.
</P>
<P>
In the morning trading, the index dropped 10 percent to
3,343.91 points, but it rebounced slightly in the afternoon
session.
</P>
<P>
For the whole day, the National-100 Index lost 283.12 points,
or 7.35 percent, from Monday's finish.
</P>
<P>
The financial index dropped to 4,217.73 points, down 338.65
points, or 7.12 percent, the industrial index declined to
2,944.31 points, down 295.26 points, or 7.67 percent, and the
service index fell to 4,191.63 points, down 327.60 points, or
6.97 percent, from Monday's finishes.
</P>
<P>
This was the second day that the Istanbul Stock Exchange has
plunged following the Monday's fall of 226.34 points from last
Friday's
</P>
<P>
Turkish investors apparently feared that the crisis in Asian
markets may spread to dampen economic activities worldwide, thus
harming Turkey's exports.
</P>
<P>
On another hand, share traders speculated that Turkey might
have to devaluate the Turkish lira in a bid to keep its exporting
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Many of the currencies in Asian markets, led by the Japanese
yen, have been tumbling in the past week due to the economic
uncertainty in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Under the present system Turkey's Central Bank allows the
Turkish lira to devalue slowly in connection with the inflation
rate of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
