<HEADLINE> Tajikistan Calls for Int'l Efforts on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Tajikistan Tuesday urged Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to use his influence in strengthening the
borders of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) with
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting chaired by Tajik President Emomli Rakhmonov, the
Tajik Military Council called on member nations of the CIS and
parties to the Collective Security Treaty to take necessary steps
to strengthen the CIS's southern borders in the wake of the
deteriorating situation in Afghanistan, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The council meeting was also attended by the country's
parliament speaker and the foreign, defense, interior and security
ministers as well as the commander of the Russian border guards in
Tajikistan, the commander of the peacekeeping force and the
commander of Russia's 201st Motorized Division.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik leaders urged the CIS Council of Defense Ministers to
meet shortly to discuss the situation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The council also appealed to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
to take urgent steps to help end hostilities in Afghanistan and
find a political settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
As large numbers of Afghan refugees move to the regions
bordering Tajikistan, Dushanbe fears a spontaneous influx of the
refugees in the country.
</P>
<P>
Some units of Russian and Tajik troops were already put on high
alert Tuesday along the Tajik borders with Afghanistan amid
reports that some Taliban fighters were sighted near the border.
</P>
<P>
The recent flare-up of fighting in northern Afghanistan has
worried Russia and the central republics bordering Afghanistan,
especially Tajikistan, which has the longest border with the
Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
In Uzbekistan, restrictions have been re-imposed on the
frontier garrison town of Termez and outsiders could not fly there
without special commission.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban fighters have reportedly captured the northern city
of Mazar-e-Sharif following their weekend offensive.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Russian Foreign Ministry Tuesday
said Russia, together with other CIS countries, has the right to
take steps to protect its borders.
</P>
<P>
"The world community must take urgent and decisive steps to
prevent expansion of the conflict in Afghanistan and its spill to
neighboring countries," Foreign Ministry spokesman Valery
Nesterushkin told a press briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
