<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2005 GMT, August 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has promised
the U.S. a change in the Likud stance towards the American
proposal for a 13 percent Israeli pullback, said a senior aide to
the Egyptian president.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, the presidential political advisor, said Monday
night that Netanyahu's promise was made to U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright during a recent contact. (Egypt-Israel-US Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Cairo-based Arab League Tuesday called for
convening an international conference on combating terrorism after
Friday's twin bombings against American embassies in two eastern
African capitals. (AL-Bombings-International Conference)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Tuesday that Israel would not object to negotiations on
formulating an international treaty to ban the production of the
fissionable material used to make unclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
But Israel Radio quoted the prime minister as telling the
cabinet that this attitude did not mean automatic Israeli support
for the final treaty. Israel still had principled objections which
it would try to clear up with the United States, he said.
(Israel-Nuclear-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- After nine consecutive days of scorching heat, the
worst heat wave in decades abated Tuesday in Cyprus leaving 56
dead, most of whom are elderly people.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's temperatures fell to 39 degrees Celsius in Nicosia, 4
degrees lower than Monday. (Cyprus-Heat Wave)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- In what regarded as a show of intention towards the
normalization of ties with Iraq, Lebanon Tuesday suggested the two
countries send officials to their respective closed embassies in
the other.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz,
Iraqi Ambassador to Jordan Nouri Ismail told reporters here that
Lebanon wants to appoint an administrative officer in its closed
embassy in Baghdad, the state-run National News agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It also hopes that Iraq do the same in order to handle
commercial services between the two countries, the ambassador
said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral ties were severed following an assassination of
the Iraqi opposition figure Taleb Suhail al-Tamimi in Beirut in
1994. (Lebanon-Iraq-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt Tuesday hosted a meeting of opposition leaders
in northern and southern Sudan on how to end the 15-year civil war
in its southern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The meeting groups John Garang, leader of the Sudanese People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), Al-Sadeq Al-Mahdi, former Sudanese Prime
Minister and leader of the Ummah Party, and Mohammed Osman
Al-Merghani, the head of the National Democratic Alliance, the
umbrella group for northern and southern Sudanese oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Deputy Prime Minister Youssef Wali represented Egypt
at the meeting, said Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
(Egypt-Sudan-Opposition Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Tuesday rejected the claim by the Afghan
Taliban militia that it did not know the whereabouts of 11 Iranian
diplomats allegedly captured by it in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Tehran radio, Iran's special envoy on
Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi said that the Iranian
diplomats, now held by Taliban in Qandahar, were sound and the
Taliban can not shirk responsibility for their safety.
</P>
<P>
The "Foreign Ministry" of Taliban regime issued a statement
earlier Tuesday saying that it did not know the whereabouts of the
11 missing Iranians. It added that if it had arrested them, they
would be tried and punished as agents of a hostile government.
(Iran-Taliban-Diplomats) 
</P>
