<HEADLINE> Clinton Friend Testifies before Grand Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Prosecutors Tuesday
questioned U.S. President Bill Clinton's friend Harry Thomason and
a White House lawyer before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
Thomason's testimony was followed by that of deputy White House
counsel Cheryl Mills. In the afternoon, a number of Secret Service
personnel were also subpoenaed to testify in the Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
After winning a court battle over attorney-client privilege,
prosecutors have begun questioning some of the White House
lawyers, including Mills.
</P>
<P>
Thomason, a Hollywood television director, emerged from the
courthouse after about 90 minutes of testimony and said he was
questioned about the time he spent in the White House last
January, when he came to help advise Clinton on damage control.
</P>
<P>
"I've always believed the president was telling the truth,"
said Thomason.
</P>
<P>
"I thought the grand jurors were nice, and the prosecutors were
courteous. And it was actually a good morning," Thomason added as
he departed for the offices of his lawyer, Robert Bennett, the
same attorney who represented Clinton in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
Independent counsel Kenneth Starr is looking into whether
Clinton and Lewinsky had sex and whether he urged her to lie about
it in the Jones lawsuit. Clinton has denied a sexual relationship
with Lewinsky, 25. But she, according to legal sources, told the
grand jurors that contrary to the president's sworn denial and her
own affidavit in January, did have a sexual relationship with him.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, obtained
permission from U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright to view
the videotape of Clinton denying under oath January 17 that he had
a sexual relationship with Lewinsky. 
</P>
</TEXT>
