<HEADLINE> Pentagon: U.S. Seeks Diplomatic Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States still seeks
a goal of reaching a diplomatic solution to the Kosovo crisis
despite the threat by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) to intervene militarily, said Pentagon on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon
said, "Our goal in Kosovo is to reach a diplomatic solution to the
problem. I think we've been very clear about that from the very
beginning."
</P>
<P>
Last week, the State Department said the alliance is finishing
a package of military intervention plans on Kosovo, demanding
Belgrade to stop its offensives against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"If there is any military involvement in Kosovo, it will be
done through NATO, not unilaterally by the United States," said
Bacon.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, U.S. Ambassador to Macedonia, Christopher Hill, was
in the provincial capital, Pristina, to meet with Ibrahim Rugova,
leader of the Kosovo Albanians and Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister
Nikola Sainovic.
</P>
<P>
Serbian officials said that ethnic Albanians guerrillas had
killed 10 policemen in Kosovo during a clash.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanian rebels are fighting for independence of
Kosovo, where 90 percent of the population are Albanians. However,
it gained no supports around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
