<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Securities Market Plunge Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian stocks continued to drop
Tuesday, with most of the blue chips sliding 10-15 percent while
some shares dropped as much as 20-25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The RTS-Interfax Composite Ruble Index was off 9.69 percent to
a record low of 27.84 points. The RTS-1-Interfax index fell 9.11
percent to 109.91 points, the lowest since May 1996, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mounting pressure for a devaluation of the ruble and the crisis
on the market in government securities would possibly force the
central bank to increase the refinancing rate, currently at 60
percent, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Fear that Russia would not be able to cope with the escalating
servicing costs on both its external and internal debt, prompted
foreign investors to sell off some Russian Eurobonds, which in
turn helped to dampen the mood of Russian investors, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russia's Deputy Finance Minister Oleg
Vyugin told Interfax that the government has set aside 2 billion
dollars for servicing domestic debt in August.
</P>
<P>
The dive Tuesday on Russian markets led to technical halts to
trading on the RTS and the Russian Stock Exchange under Federal
Securities Commission rules, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
At 18:00 Moscow time (14:00 GMT) Tuesday, Unified Energy
Systems of Russia common shares were down 10 percent to 0.0905
U.S. dollars on volume of 73.55 million shares, while Lukoil fell
12.9 percent to 5.4/5.49 dollars on 525,000 shares and Mosenergo
dropped 7.5 percent to 0.04/0.0405 dollars on 80.2 million shares.
Rostelekom fell 14 percent to 1.45/1.5 dollars on 983,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the RTS was 18.754 million dollars on Tuesday,
slightly higher than Monday's total of 15.187 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom shares, which are traded on the Moscow Stock Exchange,
fell 14.2 percent to 1.63 rubles per share on volume of 23.435
million rubles, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Market operators expect the market to continue its plunge. They
attribute it to a threat of ruble devaluation and a possible hike
of refinancing rate, both signs of weakness of the government and
the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Some also point to the shortage of rubles in the market as one
reason that caused the downward turn of the Russian securities
market.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts offer mixed predictions on the movement of
refinancing rate of the central bank. Some believe the rate would
not be raised any time soon as the central bank had already
dropped the practice of providing commercial banks loans with
securities as mortgages since late June.
</P>
<P>
Under this circumstance, they say, raising refinancing rate
would have little direct impact on the financial market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
