<HEADLINE> German States Impose Traffic Restrictions amid Heat Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Four German federal states are to
impose temporary traffic restrictions on Wednesday to reduce air
pollutions and prevent excessive concentration of ozone in the hot
summer air.
</P>
<P>
In the German states of Baden-Wuerttemberg, Hessen,
Rhineland-Palatinate and Saarland, cars without catalytic
converters will not be allowed to go onto the streets for 24 hours
up from 6 a.m. on Wednesday, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The new regulation is meant to reduce the level of summer smog
which can lead to excessive concentration of ozone above the
ground which is unhealthy to the human body.
</P>
<P>
As air temperatures soaring in Germany recently, the tolerable
maximum ozone value of 240 micrograms per cubic meter air was
surpassed in several locations in Germany on Tuesday,
meteorologists said.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday afternoon, meteorologists also reported
Germany's highest-ever air temperature of 41.2 degrees centigrade
in the Mosel River Valley. Local record-high temperatures were
also reported in many other German cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
