<HEADLINE> U.S. B-2 Stealth Bombers Return to Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force has
resumed training flights of its B-2 stealth bombers after four
days of grounding because of a problem with the crew ejection
system, the service said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"They are back to normal flying operations," said Air Force
spokesman Major Tyrone Woodyard.
</P>
<P>
The radar-avoiding bombers, built by Northrop Grumman Corp.
with a cost of some 2 billion dollars each, were all returned to
training as of Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force said last Thursday that a potential problem
associated with initiators which operate the air crew ejection
system. Parts in the ejection systems had been replaced before the
resumption of flights.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 21 stealth bombers the government planned to build
have been manufactured, but are not yet in active service. Some
ten of them have been delivered to the Air Force and are based
with the 509th Bomb Wing at Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri.
</P>
</TEXT>
