<HEADLINE> Greece to Reward People for Information to Arsonists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Greece decided Tuesday to reward
persons who provide information leading to the arrest of
arsonists.
</P>
<P>
The decision, signed by Greek Public Minister George Romeos and
Finance Undersecretary Nikolaos Christodoulakis, provides for a
reward of between 5 and 20 million drachmas (about 1.7 and 6.7
million U.S. dollars) per fire, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The reward would be given for information about fires
throughout the country since July 1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greece's Culture Ministry also declared the banning
of smoking at the country's archaeological sites and museums.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, there had been 2,700 forest fires around Greece.
Currently, some 44 forest fires were reported in the country.
</P>
<P>
Heat waves and arsonists have been blamed for the nationwide
forest fires which have destroyed over 120,000 hectares of forest
and cultivated land, homes, shops and vehicles, and left at least
six people dead.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Greek firefighters, aided by soldiers and foreign
fireplanes, have been battling the forest fires in Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
