<HEADLINE> Tunisia Voices Support for Libya on U.N. Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Terming the U.N. embargo against
Libya as "unacceptable and unjustifiable," Tunisia said Tuesday it
will stand by Libya in confronting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Hamed Karoui, prime minister of Tunisia, made the remarks upon
his arrival in Tripoli, capital of Libya, the Tunisia Africa News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
But the news agency did not say if Karoui went there by air to
break the U.N. imposed air embargo on Libya.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed the air and arms embargo on 1992 after Libya
refused to hand over two Libyans, suspected of bombing a Pan-Am
airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, for trial in the
U.S. or Britain.
</P>
<P>
Libya has insisted the trial be held in a neutral country to
ensure its justice.
</P>
<P>
Three African leaders have defied the embargo by flying to
Libya last month.
</P>
<P>
And the Organization of African Unity also made a call in June
for its members to ignore the sanctions as of September 1 if the
U.S. and Britain made no compromise.
</P>
<P>
Karoui, leading a high-level delegation on a two-day working
visit, is going to hold talks with his Libyan counterpart Mohamed
al-Mangoush on ways to enhance bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Karoui said the talks will serve as "another brick in the
palace of the fruitful cooperation and constructive integration
between the two countries in the face of regional and
international challenges." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
