<HEADLINE> S. Africa Accuses Israel of Buying Time in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki Tuesday accused Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu of buying time to implement his own programs
rather than work toward peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with visiting Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat in Cape Town, Mbeki said it was surprising that
Netanyahu had not accepted the United States' proposals aimed at
enhancing the peace process in Middle East.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Mbeki as saying
that the proposals had been accepted by the Palestinian National
Authority.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to us that all that Netanyahu is doing is to try to
buy time to implement his programs, rather than work for peace
for the whole Middle East region," said Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process remained a critical issue and
South Africa would do everything possible toward its achievement,
Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cape Town at around midnight Monday for a
three-day state visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and South African President Nelson Mandela Tuesday held
private talks about the faltering Middle East peace process and
witnessed the signing of two bilateral declarations of intent on
health and education.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders exchanged decorations. Arafat gave Mandela
the Star of Holy Jerusalem, and Mandela invested Arafat with
South Africa's highest civilian honor, the Order of Good Hope.
</P>
