<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Electoral Commission Inaugurated in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A new electoral body, the
Independent Electoral Commission (INEC) was inaugurated Tuesday
in Nigerian capital Abuja, thus kicking off another round of
transition to civil rule program by the ruling military regime.
</P>
<P>
The new electoral body has 14 members, including its Chairman,
Justice Ephraim Akpata.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration ceremony, Nigerian Head of State,
General Abdulsalam Abubakar charged the INEC to "work extremely
hard to ensure that the federal government fulfills its solemn
promise to the hand-over date of May 29, 1999."
</P>
<P>
"This is a promise we have solemnly made and it is a promise
we are committed to keep," he was quoted by the official News
Agency of Nigeria (NAN) as saying.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar asked the the new electoral body, appointed
by him last Thursday, to work out within two weeks the guidelines
for political party formation, registration and other tasks that
are relevant to a successful, free and fair electoral process
that will usher in true democracy.
</P>
<P>
In the next two weeks, INEC was also to draw up a timetable
for various elections under the transition program, including
that of local government councils, state and national assemblies,
state governors and the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
According to the new transition program announced by Abubakar
on July 20, the presidential election is to be held within the
first quarter of 1999, while the new civilian president will be
inaugurated on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar canceled all the elections held under the transition
to civil rule program of his predecessor, General Sani Abacha,
saying that it had lost all its credibility and acceptability due
to massive rigging.
</P>
<P>
The new head of state went a step further by sacking all the
five political parties as well as the National Electoral
Commission, promising a new democratization process to be
monitored by a truly independent electoral body.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's inauguration, Abubakar promised that his
government will provide the necessary legal, financial and
logistics support to ensure that the electoral commission works
effectively toward hitch-free elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
