<HEADLINE> S. Africa Duty-Bound to Support Palestine: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said Tuesday night that his country had a duty to
support the Palestinian people, who are seeking justice and
equality.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a banquet in Cape Town in honor of visiting
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, Mandela said South Africa
would play its part in ensuring that Palestine assumed its
rightful position internationally.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said South Africa, along with the rest of the world,
hoped that the deadlock in Palestinian-Israeli talks would give
way to a recognition that the security of any one nation depends
on that of others, and that no one can enjoy lasting peace while
others remain in conditions that perpetuate injustice, poverty
and insecurity.
</P>
<P>
Mandela spoke highly of the generosity of the Palestinian
people and their support for South African democratic struggle
against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
Now that South Africa had achieved freedom, "we have not
forgotten our friends and allies who helped us liberate
ourselves, " said the South African president.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was proud of being part of the international
consensus affirming the right of Palestine to self-determination
and statehood, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to playing our humble part, within the
limits of our resources, to help ensure that Palestine assumes
its rightful position in the global arena, " the 80-year-old
president said.
</P>
<P>
In response, Arafat said that South Africa's support and
backing for the Palestine's right to self-determination was
highly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
It would strengthen and solidify Palestine's position in
achieving freedom and independence, he said, adding that South
Africa's successful transition to a non-racial democracy was a
source of inspiration to the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cape Town, the legislative capital of South
Africa, Monday night for a three-day state visit to the country,
the first of its kind since the two countries formally
established diplomatic ties in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Palestinian leader had talks with Mandela, his
deputy Thabo Mbeki, and leaders of opposition parties in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Mandela also awarded Arafat South Africa's
highest honor for foreigners, the Order of Good Hope. In return,
Arafat invested his South African counterpart with Palestine's
highest decoration, the Star of Holy Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
