<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Yangtze Flood Peak Advancing Downstream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The fifth Yangtze River flood
crest passed Yichang at 8:30 pm this evening and is advancing
downstream to Shashi, all in central Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Yichang was measured at 54.03 meters, with a
flow rate of 62,800 cubic meters per second, the largest since the
flood season began. However, the city's 167-kilometer-long Yangtze
embankment has stood the flood tests.
</P>
<P>
Before the peak came, the city organized 85,000 workers to
protect the embankment at a spot where a landslide occurred this
morning.
</P>
<P>
This was brought under control 8 hours later, sources said,
adding that Yichang is preparing for another flood crest which is
now forming in the upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
To ease floodwater pressure at Jingjiang, the Qingjiang
Hydroelectric Station managed to reduce the floodwaters going
downstream in an effort to keep the water level at Shashi below 45
meters, the ceiling mark for diverting water into the Jingjiang
Diversion Zone where 330,000 people live.
</P>
<P>
The provincial Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters
has asked related areas to keep alert for possible flooding and to
reinforce dikes and embankments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
