<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The chief of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) expressed deep concern on Wednesday over continuing
fighting in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The NATO secretary general, Javier Solana, told the weekly
North Atlantic Council of Ambassadors that he was "deeply
concerned by the continuing violence in Kosovo and its effect on
the civilian population of the region of which (Yugoslav President
Slobodan) Milosevic bears a heavy responsibility."
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief stressed that the western military alliance is
closely monitoring the developing situation in Kosovo, where
Yugoslavian forces have clashed with the ethnic Albanian majority
who are seeking independence from Belgrade and integration into
neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO fully supports the efforts of the
international community to encourage negotiations for a solution
to the conflict. (NATO-Kosovo)
