<HEADLINE> Mainland Visitors' Spending in HK Remains Biggest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Spending by visitors from the
Chinese mainland remained the biggest contributor to Hong Kong's
tourism receipts from January to June this year.
</P>
<P>
Their spending in Hong Kong accounted for 26.6 percent of the
total, according to figures released by the Hong Kong Tourist
Association here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The total spending by visitors to Hong Kong registered a
36.5-percent drop to 24.6 billion HK dollars (3.15 billion U.S.
dollars) during the period.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan took second place, followed by the Americas and Europe,
Africa and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The drop in visitor spending reflected the fall in tourist
arrivals.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, total tourism receipts fell by 35.6
percent to a total of 25.6 billion HK dollars (3.28 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Other major factors that contributed to the fall in spending
include the currency depreciation in Asian markets, which has
considerably lowered the spending power of visitors from those
countries, lower hotel rates, the reduction in prices for shopping
items and a shorter average length of stay by visitors, the
association said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
