<HEADLINE> Northwest China's Joint Venture Produces First Auto Engine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The first 2-liter 4G6
multi-valve auto engine rolled off the production line today at
the Aerospace-Mitsubishi Engine Manufacturing Co. Ltd. in
Shenyang, capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The company is expected to develop a production capacity of
150,000 auto engines ranging from 2 liters to 2.4 liters by
2003. The engines are said to be applicable for vans, cars, jeeps
and mini-buses, said a company source.
</P>
<P>
Aerospace-Mitsubishi Engine Manufacturing Co. Ltd., founded one
year ago, is a joint venture begun by five companies from China,
Japan and Malaysia at a cost of 2.2 billion yuan. All technologies
used will be imported from Mitsubishi companies.
</P>
<P>
The five companies are China Aerospace Automobile Industrial
Corporation, Shenyang Construction Investment Company, two
Mitsubishi companies, and a company from Malaysia, with China
Aerospace Automobile Industrial Corporation holding a 30 percent
interest.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Guozhong, Chairman of the Board of the joint
venture, the company is now engaged in the construction of new
workshops, the purchase of production equipment, localization of
spare parts, consumer research, and staff training, and will start
formal production in 1999.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the localization rate of the joint venture
in producing auto engines will be 50 percent, and will reach 85
percent by 2002.  
</P>
</TEXT>
