<HEADLINE> Mubarak Stresses Need of Maintaining Sudan's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
reiterated Wednesday the need of maintaining Sudan's territorial
integrity and reinforcing efforts to end decades of fighting in
this neighboring state.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the remarks in the northern resort of Alexandria
during his meeting with Sudanese opposition leaders, who began
their meetings with Egyptian officials in Cairo Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Sudanese government and various opposition
factions to exert serious efforts in order to achieve unity.
</P>
<P>
"All Sudanese popular forces should be unified to drive back
threats facing their country ... Egypt is determined to back all
efforts exerted in this regard," said the president.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's meeting was attended by John Garang, leader of the
biggest rebel group the Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA),
Al-Sadeq Al-Mahdi, former Sudanese Prime Minister and leader of
the Ummah Party, and Mohammed Osman Al-Merghani, the head of the
Democratic Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo and Alexandria meetings are part of Egypt's bid to
bridge the gaps between the opposition and Khartoum on one hand
and among the opposition factions on the other.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Garang Tuesday, Egyptian Deputy Prime
Minister Youssef Wali said Cairo is eager to offer help to Sudan's
famine-stricken south.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has been fighting for autonomy of the south from Sudan
since 1983. Fightings combined with perennial famines have claimed
more than 1.5 million lives, most of them civilians.
</P>
<P>
The latest series of meetings were held after peace talks
between the Sudanese government and the opposition in the
Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa ended Friday without progress.
</P>
<P>
After four days of talks, differences remain on issues of
cease-fire, border demarcation of southern Sudan, the relationship
between religion and state, and the referendum on
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Egypt have long been at odds over a border dispute
and have been accusing each other of harboring rebel militants and
opposition factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
