<HEADLINE> Those Disrupting Flood-Fighting to Be Punished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's Court
today issued a notice calling on courts in flood-ravaged regions
to work around the clock and punish those disrupting the
efforts to fight the floods and protect the lives and property of
the people.
</P>
<P>
The notice stressed that courts at all levels should give
priority to cases occurring amid the flood-fighting, and
especially cases of destruction of public facilities, stealing,
robbing or raping flood victims, dereliction of duty and
misappropriation of relief funds and goods, and spreading rumors
or hoarding and profiteering.
</P>
<P>
The notice requests courts in flood-ravaged regions to pick out
typical cases and openly report those cases to frighten the
criminals and encourage the people fighting the floods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Commission For Discipline Inspection and
the Ministry of Supervision today jointly issued another notice,
calling on Party members and government officials in flood-hit
regions to hold fast to their positions and be poised to sacrifice
even their lives for the sake of the people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
