<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Deeply Concerned Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The chief of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) expressed deep concern on Wednesday
over continuing fighting in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The NATO secretary general, Javier Solana, told the weekly
North Atlantic Council of Ambassadors that he was "deeply
concerned by the continuing violence in Kosovo and its effect on
the civilian population of the region of which (Yugoslav President
Slobodan) Milosevic bears a heavy responsibility."
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief stressed that the western military alliance is
closely monitoring the developing situation in Kosovo, where
Yugoslavian forces have clashed with the ethnic Albanian majority
who are seeking independence from Belgrade and integration into
neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO fully supports the efforts of the
international community to encourage negotiations for a solution
to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general told the ambassadors from member states
that NATO's military authorities had been authorized to informally
approach nations on the forces they would be ready to contribute
to possible air operations in Kosovo, should the occasion arise.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's council meeting, held during the month-long summer
recess of the alliance, reviewed NATO's military planning for a
full range of options aimed at bringing an end to the fighting in
the Yugoslav province, and creating conditions for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Solana said the options included the use of ground as well as
air power.
</P>
<P>
NATO, to demonstrate its readiness for deployment in the
Balkans, conducted an airborne joint exercise in mid-June in
Albania and Macedonia, both bordering Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But the western military alliance failed to get an action
mandate from either the United Nations Security Council or the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Russia, the Cold-war foe of NATO, strongly opposed the use of
force by the bloc in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
