<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Foreign MPs' Visits to North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus on Wednesday protested
the recent visits by foreign parliament members to northern
Cyprus, which is controlled by its Turkish Cypriot rivals.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' House of Representatives made the protest in a
statement issued in response to a Turkish Cypriot press report
Tuesday that six Albanian parliament members are currently visiting
the north of the divided Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The statement denounced the Albanian MPs' visit to northern
Cyprus, the third in one week by foreign parliament members, as
"part of Turkish Cypriots' move to gain international recognition."
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament from Italy and Kyrgyzstan also paid a
visit to northern Cyprus last week.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Cyprus had sent a letter of protest to
Italian President of the Chamber of Deputies Luciano Violante.
</P>
<P>
In his reply, Violante noted that the tour of Italian
parliament members was unofficial and private, and the Italian
Parliament does not recognize the entity in the "occupied areas of
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus will also make representations to the Albanian and
Kyrgyz parliaments over the visits, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is only recognized
by their closest ally Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
