<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Bring Back Remains of Bombing Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright left for Germany Wednesday to bring back the remains of
U.S. victims of last week's embassy bombing in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
She planned to visit 10 hospitalized Americans and Kenyans
injured in the bombing, that killed more than 240 people,
including 12 Americans, and injured well over 5,000. Albright will
bring back 10 of the 12 remains.
</P>
<P>
"I go secure in the knowledge that America will never be
intimidated or back down in the face of terrorists," Albright said
before departing from Andrews Air Force Base, near Washington.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of Albright's departure, the State Department
announced that "there may be a threat to U.S. interests in Egypt,
Malaysia and Yemen that could include attacks on buildings."
</P>
<P>
Americans in the three countries were advised to be careful. A
senior U.S. official said the statement was based on "credible
information," but he declined to provide further details.
</P>
<P>
In the face of increased threats, the U.S. State Department has
decided to shut half a dozen embassies and some embassies would
have to be relocated to guard against terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make sure all our embassies can meet an adequate
standard," Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
