<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The number foreign tourists visiting Egypt this year
is expected to rise to 3.25 million, an increase of 8.3 percent
from 1997, the Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Egyptian National Assembly predicted the
revenues of tourism could reach 10.3 billion Egyptian pounds (3
billion U.S. dollars), an increase of some 800 million pounds (233
million dollars) from last year.
</P>
<P>
The report said the volume of investment in tourism projects
this year is estimated at about 4.8 billion pounds (1.4 billion
dollars), of which 4.6 billion pounds (1.3 billion dollars) are
spent on private projects.
</P>
<P>
JEDDA -- President of the Islamic Development Bank Ahmed
Mohamed Ali opened in Jedda Monday a meeting of regional
organizations of the bank's member states to discuss the
inter-state trade among the Organization of Islamic Conference
(OIC), the Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which is due to end Wednesday, was attended by OIC
representatives as well as the action group in charge of examining
the prospects of promoting inter-state trade among the Bank's
member states.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Petroleum Minister Hamdi Banbi has said that
demand for natural gas in Egypt will reach 52 billion cubic meters
by the year 2017, the Al Hayat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He added that 485 kilometers of pipelines will be extended for
the transport of natural gas to a number of governorates in lower
and upper Egypt and Oyoun Moussa in Sinai, raising the demand to
3.1 million cubic feet per day.
</P>
<P>
He further indicated that planned investments for these
projects will reach 1.3 billion pounds (384 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 577 kilometers of pipelines will be extended over the
period from 2002 to 2017, expanding the length of the national
transport network for natural gas to 4,400 kilometers, a 50
percent increase of the present figures. By then, 38 million cubic
meters per day will be provided to meet the needs of the
production and service sectors in the new cities.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Dubai's gold imports during the first six months of
the current year have dropped because of the measures taken by
the Indian government to liberalize trade in the precious yellow
metal, the Al Hayat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But officials of the World Gold Council anticipated that the
Gulf emirate will remain the biggest center for gold transactions
in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
