<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Warns of AIDS Epidemic in Estonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- An expert has urged the Estonian
government to take more steps in containing the spread of AIDS,
saying that the Baltic nation is on the verge of an AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Nelli Kalikova, head of the country's center for the
prevention of AIDS, told the Baltic News Service (BNS) Tuesday
that lack of sex education and growing number of drug addicts were
the main causes of AIDS in Estonia.
</P>
<P>
She said official statistics on the number of carriers of HIV,
the virus that causes the deadly disease, and the death rate among
AIDS patients does not reflect the actual situation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, Estonia registered 79 HIV carriers, 13 of whom
already died, but the actual numbers are at least five times
higher, Kalikova said.
</P>
<P>
"For a country with a population of just 1.5 million, this is
very serious," she said.
</P>
<P>
Kalikova said the country's incidence of venereal diseases
such as syphilis, gonorrhea, hepatitis B and C is also growing,
mainly as a result of syringe sharing by drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
"Drug addiction has infected all sections of the population,"
Kalikova said. "During a recent police raid, drug addicts were
found even in the park of the presidential palace."
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Russia, there were better news about AIDS. The
number of newly registered HIV carriers there, at 1,468, dropped
16 percent in the first six months of this year, said First Deputy
Health Minister Gennady Onischenko on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 8,956 HIV carriers have been registered in Russia
since 1987, the Interfax news agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
