<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Flooding at Nenjiang River? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Why is record flooding rolling
high along the Nenjiang River in northeast China at a time when
the water level on the Yangtze River is receding?
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists attribute this directly to continuous rainfall
and incoming water from the river's tributaries.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall at the Nenjiang River has been caused by the same
atmospheric conditions prevailing over the Yangtze River, so the
two areas have had rainfall at almost exactly the same time.
</P>
<P>
The abnormal climate across the world brought about by El Nino
in 1997, the strongest such in a century, triggered off China's
unusual flooding this year, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-June, the weather conditions in Eurasia has been
blocking rain clouds from moving northward, while rain clouds
over China have been stopped from moving eastward, causing
torrential rains in the two river valleys.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China has had more rainfall during this year's flood
season, in particular over the past week, when the two watersheds
were hit by torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Central Meteorological Station forecasts that the
atmospheric circulation will improve, and rainfall in northeast
China is expected to ease up in the next few days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
