<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Machine Triggers Arafat Security Scare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The parcel that triggered a
security scare in South Africa's parliamentary complex in Cape Town
ahead of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's arrival contained no bomb
or explosives, officials confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The parcel contained a coffee machine sent by a Cape Town company
to President Nelson Mandela's parliamentary advisor Ahmed Kathrada as
a surprise birthday gift, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's office said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The parcel was detonated at the gates of Mandela's Cape Town
office, Tuynhuys, by the bomb disposal unit of the South African
police.
</P>
<P>
"Following the detonations, the bomb experts have confirmed that
the parcel did not contain any bomb or explosive device," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Their actions, however, were justified in the context of the
uncertainty around the content of the parcel, and the detonation was
necessary as a precautionary measure."
</P>
<P>
The controlled explosion reverberated through the
parliamentary complex at about 11.30 a.m. (0930 GMT), amid
tightened security ahead of Arafat's arrival at parliament, South
African Press Association (SAPA) said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was due to meet National Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala
and address a joint sitting of both houses of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Tight security has characterized Arafat's visit to Cape Town,
with members of the VIP protection unit and police out in full
force, a helicopter hovering above the city, and snipers on the
roof of parliament, according to SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is on African National Congress business in Pietersburg and
was not present at Tuynhuys Wednesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
