<HEADLINE> Manila Finalizes Screening of Bond Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Department of
Finance has already finalized the screening of proposals for the
issuance of bonds, the Philippine News Agency said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu as saying
that in spite of the depreciation of the peso, "the Philippines
continued to enjoy a fair spread in its planned bond offering from
investors who made firm offers."
</P>
<P>
Fourteen foreign investment banks had submitted proposals on
the issuance of government bonds, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu revealed that the government has chosen Goldman Sachs,
J. P. Morgan and Warburg Dillon Read to underwrite a two-phased
bond offering in the international market.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would do two bond offerings in sequence
with the first possibly in September and the second in October.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds of the bond offerings are intended to help finance
the country's budgetary requirements, he said, adding that the
government hopes to raise at least 500 million U.S. dollars from
the offerings.
</P>
<P>
One of the offerings would involve the issuance of U.S.
dollar-denominated floating yield securities in the global market
and the other the issuance of euro-denominated fixed rate
securities in the European market.
</P>
<P>
The two bond offerings would be the first for the Estrada
administration and would prove the continuing attractiveness of
the Philippines to international investors in spite of the
continuing crisis, Espiritu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
