<HEADLINE> Lesotho Soldiers Fire Stun Grenades at Protesters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho army fired stun
grenades at protesters outside King Letsie III's palace in Maseru
Wednesday afternoon after the crowd defied an order to disperse.
</P>
<P>
There was chaos and panic when soldiers fired and it was not
known whether there was any injuries, South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted opposition parties spokeswoman Monica
Mopeli as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They started shooting at about 2.10 p.m. (1210 GMT) and it is
chaos here with people running in all directions. We have not
established how many, if any, people have been injured at this stage,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
The army action followed an earlier order by army chief
Lieutenant-Colonel Makhula Motakeng for the protesters to disperse.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties defied the order, saying several issues
should be cleared before they could leave the royal palace.
</P>
<P>
These included opposition parties' representativeness in the
Independent Electoral Commission panel that is to re-count the votes
of the May 23 general election.
</P>
<P>
The protesters are demanding the king to intervene in the political
impasse and overturn the results of the election. But the king refused
to be involved.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili Wednesday called for calm
and restraint.
</P>
<P>
He called on supporters of his ruling Lesotho Congress for
Democracy (LCD) to remain calm and refrain from doing anything that
could worsen the situation.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that as leader of the LCD it had come
to his attention that party members had been provoked and
incensed by the situation which faced the government they had
elected.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal to them to exercise restraint until the peaceful and
legal process agreed by the political party leaders and the government
is completed," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to an agreement between his government and
opposition parties on the establishment of a southern African
committee to probe into election fraud allegations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, however, appeared to be unable to appease the
protesters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
