<HEADLINE> OAU Leader Appeals for Joint Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary General of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU), Salim Ahamed Salim,
appealed to the international community Wednesday to make joint
efforts in the fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Salim made the appeal in Dar es Salaam while visiting the
wrecked U.S. embassy in Tanzania, and the neighboring Nigerian
embassy, Algerian ambassador's residence and the French embassy
which were affected by the powerful blast.
</P>
<P>
Salim said Tanzania, Kenya, the United States and other relevant
parties in the world should work together in the investigation into
the two separate bombing incidents in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam last
Friday, which killed more than 200 people and injured over 5,000
others.
</P>
<P>
He said terrorists are shifting their targets of attack, but most
of the victims have been innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism cannot be left be uncurbed, he said, and called on people
who have clues to inform the police as soon as possible so that the
criminals behind the blast could be brought to justice at an early
date.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian embassy which is still in chaos has moved to the
Karibu Hotel in the city to resume office service, while repairs
of the Algerian ambassador's residence are to be completed in one
or two days.
</P>
<P>
The French embassy is waiting for experts to evaluate its loss
arising from the blast. 
</P>
