<HEADLINE> Singapore Calls for Upholding ASEAN Principles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong Wednesday called upon ASEAN countries to uphold its core
principles and goals while concentrating on solving serious
economic problems facing them.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a banquet in honor of visiting Lao Prime Minister
Sisavath Keobounphan, Goh said, "ASEAN is currently facing many
serious challenges. While ASEAN should develop new responses to
these challenges, we must not unwittingly undermine the core
principles that have kept ASEAN united through the past 31 years."
</P>
<P>
"It is at such times of great uncertainty that we should
together keep faith with ASEAN's core principles," he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, "To restore confidence in the ASEAN
economies, the realization of AFTA (ASEAN Free Trade Area) has
become even more urgent. Advancing the AFTA timetable will send a
powerful signal to international investors of the determination of
ASEAN countries to open their economies to trade and investment."
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
On the regional situation, Prime Minister Goh noted, "The
region is in the grips of a financial and economic crisis."
</P>
<P>
"In many other countries, the economic crisis has weakened
their political and social fabric," he said. "Externally, the
crisis has reduced the international prestige of this region."
</P>
<P>
"Singapore remains positive about the long-term prospect of the
region," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He also made clear that the region's inherent strengths and
resilience are widely acknowledged, saying, "We can turn the
financial crisis to advantage, by confronting difficult economic
issues and introducing much-needed measures to reform and
strengthen our economic and legal framework."
</P>
<P>
"The regional crisis also shows how interdependent and
interconnected our economies are and how important it is for us to
work together to overcome it," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Lao Prime Minister Sisavath arrived here this morning for a
three-day official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
