<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Refuse Transfer Station Opened in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A refuse transfer station
capable of processing 2,500 tons of waste per day and serving a
population of 1.5 million people in its catchment was officially
opened here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Located at the West Kowloon Reclamation Area, the transfer
station, the largest of its kind in terms of waste handling
capacity, was built at a capital cost of 627 million HK dollars
(80.38 million U.S. dollars) and with an annual operating cost of
about 77 million HK dollars (9.87 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Michael Stokoe, acting director of Environmental Protection,
said at the opening ceremony that this station is designed with a
high tolerance to accommodate short-term surges and irregularities
in waste throughput to suit the unique situation in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
All the wastes received at the station are compacted into
specially-designed sealed containers which will be transferred by
marine vessels to a landfill in West New Territories for final
disposal.
</P>
<P>
Stokoe said the newly-built refuse transfer station is
operating to very high environmental standards whereby all air and
effluent emissions from the facility would be properly treated
before discharge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
