<HEADLINE> Israel: Sanction on UNITA Helpful for Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli government has
decided to observe the United Nations resolution of imposing
sanctions on the rebels in Angola, wishing that it may help the
materialization of real peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Zeev Boim, a parliament member of the ruling Likud group,
made the remark on arriving here Wednesday for his three-day
visit aimed at promoting cooperation between Angola and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Boim said that though Israel is one of the biggest diamond
processors in the world, it has informed the United Nations of
its support for the sanction on the diamond-rich southern African
country. Israel is one of the earliest countries to give active
respond to the U.N. decision, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. passed a resolution on June 12, banning all the bank
accounts of the leaders of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) abroad, and banning any import of
diamond without the permission of the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution also bans any trade activities involving
mining equipment and labor service in areas not controlled by
the government.
</P>
<P>
Boim said Israel has some thing in common as it is trying to
end the war with Arabians and win peace as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel and Angola are both concerned about the
peace process in their respective countries, they both want
to realize peace in their countries, but the road of peace is
not a smooth sailing.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Angola established diplomatic relations in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
