<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Rocket Explodes During Lift-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A United States military
rocket carrying a classified spy satellite for the Pentagon
exploded during lift-off in Florida on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force's giant Titan 4 rocket, launched at 7:30 a.m.,
one-and-a-half hours late because of fueling problems, split apart
about a minute into flight, showering debris over the Atlantic
Ocean, the Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
The boom could be heard miles away. But the Air Force said
there were no injuries and no danger to nearby residents in Cape
Canaveral, on the east coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
Fumes from the exploded fuel wafted out to sea and dispersed
within a half-hour.
</P>
<P>
The Titan 4, powered by solid-fuel boosters, is the largest
unmanned rocket built by Lockhead Martin Corp. in the United
States. It was carrying a secret satellite for the National
Reconnaissance Office, reportedly costing about one billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rocket should have been launched in late July, but was
grounded so workers could repair torn insulation on the rocket's
upper stage.
</P>
<P>
The last time a rocket exploded at Cape Canaveral Air Station
was in January 1997, when a Delta blew up seconds into flight. In
August 1993, a Titan 4 rocket blew up at Vandenberg Air Force Base
in California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
