<HEADLINE> Saudi King Undergoes Gall-bladder Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian King Fahd Bin
Abdel Aziz underwent a successful operation to remove his
gall-bladder earlier Wednesday, the royal court announced in a
statement in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the king was in good health after the
operation, which was conducted at the King Faisal Hospital in
Riyadh by an American surgeon from Duke University in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
A team of Saudi doctors assisted in the operation, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi monarch was admitted to the hospital 10 days
ago, where he underwent a colon operation on August 3.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd, 77, was admitted to hospital last March for
treating an infection on the gall bladder.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the king's health suffered from fatigue and stress.
Upon the doctors' advice, he spent a three-month period of
recuperation, during which the state affairs were managed by Crown
Prince Abdullah Bin Abdel Aziz.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd, who took power in 1982, is the fifth monarch of
Saudi Arabia, which was founded by his late father, Abdel Aziz
Al-Saud in 1931. 
</P>
