<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Restores Freedom for Trade Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Government of Nigeria
has signed into law a new decree restoring freedom for trade
unions in the country as part of its efforts for national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The decree was signed by Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar shortly before he administered the oath of
office on members of the Independent National Electoral
Commission on Tuesday in the Nigerian capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The new decree also gave a legal backing to the reconstitution
of the Academic Staff Union of Universities which was also banned
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government abrogated the decrees outlawing the
Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC), the National Union of Petroleum and
Natural Gas Workers and Petroleum and Natural Gas Senior Staff
Association of Nigeria in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The repealed decrees were promulgated in 1994 after a
protracted oil workers' strike which almost paralyzed the
country's economy under the late General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The oil workers in Nigeria went on a nationwide strike in
protest against the annulment of the June 12, 1993 presidential
election which was believed to have been won by late Bashorun
Moshood Abiola, a renowned opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
Since then, a series of sanctions have been imposed on Nigeria
by western countries and international organizations, especially
the International Labor Organization.
</P>
<P>
In response to the government action, Adms Aliyu Oshiomhole,
General Secretary of the National Union of Textile Garment and
Tailoring Workers, said the government gesture is commendable.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy with this development since we have been asking
for the abolishment of all obnoxious decrees promulgated to
suppress labor," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have every reason to believe that the government will keep
to its promise. I have confidence after all the government has
started restoring peace to labor in the country," the labor
leader added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
