<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Unemployment Falls to Lowest for over Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment rate in Britain has
fallen to the lowest level for more than a decade, according to
official figures published here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both the number of people claiming benefit and the total
looking for work were lower in July, according to figures from the
Office for National Statistics. This is expected to dispel
somewhat fears of a gloomy outlook for the jobs market following a
series of recent job loss announcements.
</P>
<P>
The government's preferred measure of counting unemployment, or
the ILO system, which includes people not eligible for benefit,
fell by 62,000 in the three months to June to 1,802,000. This is
the lowest total since the ILO definition was first introduced in
1984.
</P>
<P>
The ILO unemployment rate is now 6.2 percent, down from 6.5
percent in the previous three months and 7.2 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said improvement in the
labor market is continuing, although at a slower rate.
</P>
<P>
The figures saw a fall in the number of 18 to 24-year-olds,
including students, signing on for benefit, indicating that the
tighter benefit regime is having an effect.
</P>
<P>
General productivity was 1.4 percent higher in the first three
months of the year compared to a year ago, but manufacturing
productivity fell by 0.5 percent in the three months to June.
</P>
<P>
Also, figures for average earnings showed a rise of 5 percent
in the year to May, down 0.4 percent from the previous month, the
lowest increase since February.
</P>
<P>
However, private sector pay rises continued to outstrip
increases in the public sector, though the figures showed the gap
was closing.
</P>
<P>
Previous monthly rises in average earnings were a major factor
in the Bank of England's decision to increase interest rates
because it feared higher wages would lead to a rise in inflation.
</P>
<P>
The figures surprised many economists, who generally painted a
bleak prospect for the economy, the labor market in particular, as
a growing number of manufacturers are laying off workers, blaming
high interest rates and the strength of sterling.
</P>
<P>
Union leaders have called for the government to act to counter
the strength of the pound, but the government has defended its
economic policies, offering the prospect of a "turn around" for
business by the beginning of next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
