<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siberian Tigers Being Protected Against Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Prolonged rain storms and
flooding have abruptly raised the water level of the Songhuajiang
River at Harbin in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, posing
a serious threat to the 52 Siberian tigers in the province's
Siberian tiger breeding center.
</P>
<P>
"The river's water level was only one meter lower than the
northern embankment yesterday afternoon, and the embankment was
kept intact thanks to the efforts of hundreds of people," said Li
Wei, office director of the Siberian tiger breeding center.
</P>
<P>
The center, the largest in the world attempting to adapt
Siberian tigers to wild life, is located only 400 meters from the
river's northern embankment.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the Songhuajiang River at Harbin, capital of
Heilongjiang Province, rose to 118.96 meters this afternoon, and
people are busy consolidating the dikes, said an official with the
city's flood control center.
</P>
<P>
"The city government is taking emergency measures to
consolidate the dikes, and preparations are underway to evacuate
the tigers to another wild animal breeding center in Henghedaozi,
more than 200 kilometers from here," said Liu Xingchen, head of
the breeding center.
</P>
<P>
The river's water level is expected to rise again when a new
crest approachs this section in the near future, the city's flood
control center said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Siberian tigers in the breeding center are
enjoying a cool summer and paying no attention to the possible
danger. The No. 52 tiger killed two oxen today, and the No. 37
tiger baths itself each day in a pond.
</P>
<P>
The Siberian tiger is one of the most endangered animals, with
only about 300 left in the world. China set up a Siberian tiger
breeding center in 1986 and has now bred more than 100 tigers. The
center in northern Harbin was established in 1996 to train the
tigers born in captivity to adapt to life in the wild when they
are eventually returned to their natural habitat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
