<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Major Power Plant Starts Generating Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The first generator at the
Ertan Hydroelectric Power Station, which will be the largest
to be completed in China this century, began generating
power on a trial basis at 5:20 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
The 550,000-kw generator is capable of producing 15 million kwh
of electricity a day. It is presently the largest hydroelectric
power generator in China.
</P>
<P>
Liu Junfeng, general manager of the Ertan Hydro-power
Development Corporation, said the operation of the first generator
indicates that each auxiliary power plant project has met the
prescribed technical specifications and requirements, and its
operation will help relieve energy pressure in central and western
China.
</P>
<P>
Work on the main part of the Ertan station began on September
14, 1991. The Ertan Hydro-electric Power Station is the second
largest hydro-power project in China following that at the Three
Gorges on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Located on the Yalong River in southwest China's Sichuan
Province, Ertan will have 6 generating units, each with a capacity
of 550,000 kilowatts, said Liu, adding that the project is
expected to be complete next year.
</P>
<P>
By that time, the Ertan will be generating 17 billion kwh of
electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
The Yalong River, a tributary on the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River, originates in the Bayan Khara Mountains in
northwestern Qinghai Province. It flows mainly through Sichuan
Province, and generators with a combined generating capacity of 24
million kilowatts can be installed along the river.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the first generator at Ertan is now the largest in
the country; and the second one, whose installation will be
finished in two days, will be put into operation in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
