<HEADLINE> First-half Tourism Receipts Fall in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong saw a sharp drop in
total tourism receipts in the first half of this year as visitor
arrivals faltered, the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA)
announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, total tourism receipts fell by 35.6
percent on a year-on-year basis to 25.6 billions (3.28 billion
U.S. dollars). Spending by visitors tumbled by 36.5 percent to
24.6 billion HK dollars (3.15 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The HKTA said that the decline in visitor spending echoed the
fall in arrivals, which went down by 21 percent over the first six
months. Currency depreciation in Asia also considerably reduced
the purchasing power of visitors from the region as they stayed
shorter and spent less.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the HKTA showed that visitors from the
Chinese mainland remained the biggest contributor, whose spending
accounted for 26.6 percent of the total. In terms of actual per
capita expenditure, visitors from the Americas took the lead with
an average spending of 5,779 HK dollars (740 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Shopping remained to top the expenditure category, accounting
for almost half of the total spending by inbound tourists,
according to the HKTA.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's total tourism receipts reached 72.1 billion HK
dollars (9.24 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
