<HEADLINE> Hydropower Facilities Join Flood Relief Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Water conservancy and hydropower
stations in Sichuan Province have engaged in active efforts to
divert the heaviest flooding in 44 years to alleviate serious
threats to areas on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
The facilities have either stored and diverted over
11 billion cu.m. of floodwaters surging down the Yangtze River
throughout the summer, according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
The province, located on the upper reaches of the river, has
experienced 14 heavy rainstorms since June. All major water
conservancy and hydropower stations in Sichuan have been urged to
engage in a maximum effort to divert water and reduce the impact of
flooding on the lower reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
For example, the partially completed Ertan Hydropower Station,
the second largest hydropower station in China, stored 3.6 billion
cu.m. of water during this summer's third heaviest flood period on
August 10.
</P>
<P>
The province sent 10 lifeboats to Jiangxi Province to assist
with flood relief efforts on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
