<HEADLINE> Lesotho Protesters Defy Army Order to Disperse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred protesters
outside Lesotho King Letsie III's palace in Maseru remained in
defiance of an order from the army to disperse on Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted opposition
Basotho National Party official Bareng Sekhonyana as saying that
there were a number of issues that needed to be resolved before
the protesters could disperse.
</P>
<P>
These included opposition parties' representation in the
Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) panel which is to re-count
the votes of the May general election.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to disperse here until these issues are
cleared to our satisfaction. We want representatives in the IEC
because if they re-count the votes alone, they would just confirm
the (initial) results of the elections," Sekhonyana said.
</P>
<P>
He said these issues had been raised during discussions with
the army chief, Lieutenant-Colonel Makhula Motakeng, and
opposition parties were awaiting his response.
</P>
<P>
"We also informed him that this is a political problem and
that he should not intervene. The protesters are orderly and they
are not causing any damage to the shops in the area."
</P>
<P>
The order to disperse was issued by Motakeng and broadcast by
a radio station Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
When the protesters refused to leave on Wednesday morning,
troops moved in and surrounded the palace and the protesters.
</P>
<P>
Sekhonyana said there were about 500 protesters outside the
palace gates. More protesters were being barred by police from
joining the protest.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy swept 79 of 80
parliamentary seats in the May 23 election. But opposition
parties had refused to accept the results, saying the election
was rigged in favor of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
Through the mediation of South African Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki, the Lesotho government and opposition parties agreed
Monday on the establishment of a southern African committee to
probe into election fraud allegations.
</P>
<P>
However, it appeared that the agreement was unable to appease
protesters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
