<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Rise 1.17 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks rebounded
slightly Wednesday as fears about the crippling Japanese yen
eased.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index gained 79.53 points, or 1.17 percent
Wednesday to finish the day at 6,859.48.
</P>
<P>
The rally followed a plunge on Tuesday, when the 33 blue-chip
index tumbled to a five-year low of 6,779.95 on currency woes. The
yen hit an eight-year low of 147 to one U.S. dollar Tuesday,
triggering an all-round retreat in major stock markets in the globe.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese currency turned stronger Wednesday to 145 yen to
the greenback, market sources said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the Hong Kong bourse picked up to 5.552 billion HK
dollars (711 million U.S. dollars) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Utility shares led Wednesday's advance by surging more than
three percent, and banking counters posted a one-percent increase.
Property stocks fell 1.24 percent, while H shares and red chips
stayed calm.  
</P>
