<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranians Scuffle with Pakistani Embassy Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 riot policemen with
sticks and shields Wednesday morning rushed to surround the
Pakistani embassy here and pushed back protestors after scuffles
broke out.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators were demanding the release of 11 Iranian
diplomats, an official news agency IRNA reporter and 32 drivers,
allegedly captured by the Afghan Taliban in northern Afghanistan
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The angry demonstrators argued with police officers while
others shouted anti-Taliban and anti-Pakistan slogans. The
situation came under control after about 10 minutes and an IRNA
reporter who forced his way into the embassy was released by
embassy staff.
</P>
<P>
With his trousers torn, Abolfazl Shaker said that he was beaten
by a dozen of embassy staff members who struck him against the
gate, breaking the glass of the gate.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had no intention to enter the embassy but
wanted to ask the ambassador to answer questions of the
demonstrators. He was dragged into the embassy when he pushed open
the entrance gate.
</P>
<P>
Iran has said that it held the Taliban and Pakistan, who is
widely believed to be supporting the Islamic student militia,
responsible for the safety of the Iranians. They were reportedly
taken captive after the Taliban forces seized Mazar-e-Sharif, the
main stronghold of opposition Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The more than 100 demonstrators included IRNA staff, wives and
relatives of the IRNA correspondent and drivers.
</P>
<P>
Before they dispersed, the protestors issued a statement,
condemning the Taliban for capturing Iranian reporter and
diplomats and urging for their immediate release.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban announced on Tuesday that they did not
arrest any Iranian diplomats and the Iranian consulate in
Mazar-e-Sharif had been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic student militia said if the Iranians are arrested,
they will not be recognized as diplomats and will be tried and
punished as agents of a hostile government.
</P>
<P>
Iran rejected the Taliban claim, and called its acts as a
violation of international laws and norms. It urged Islamabad to
use its influence to ensure the safety and release of the Iranian
nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani embassy said in a press release Tuesday saying it
was not be responsible for developments in Afghanistan but will
render every possible assistance to ensure the safety of the
Iranians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
