<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey may face a ban on exporting honey to the
European Union (EU) by the end of this year if it does not refrain
from practicing its traditional ways in the apiculture, the Daily
News reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The German Honey Association (GHA) has warned Turkey against
continuing use chemicals that could damage human health in honey
production.
</P>
<P>
GHA is charged with setting up a system to monitor the imports
of animal products, including honey, to the EU market.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sells about 50 million U.S. dollars worth of honey to EU
countries each year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's tourism revenues have grown by 25 percent
so far this year compared with the same period last year, the
Daily Star newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Lebanese Tourism Minister Nicolas Fattoush as
saying that the revenues this year are expected to stand at 1.7
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Both Iraq and Jordan have agreed to import Lebanon's
pears and potatoes in the coming months, Lebanese Minister of
Agriculture Shawki Fakhoury has said.
</P>
<P>
During the period from September to January, Jordan is expected
to buy as many Lebanese pears as possible provided the fruits meet
the quality requirements of the kingdom, Fakhoury said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has the intention to import Lebanese potatoes during this
month and the next, he added.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon will sell 50 million dollars worth of goods
to Iraq in the fourth phase of the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program
starting from early last June under contracts signed between the
two Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Iraqi Ambassador to Jordan Nouri Ismail said after
meeting with Lebanese Agriculture Minister Shawki Fakhoury on
Monday that Lebanon is planning to increase this amount to 100
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraqi Minister of Agriculture Abdil-Ilah Hamid Muhammed
Saleh is expected to visit Lebanon next month for the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
