<HEADLINE> Floods Endanger Provincial Capital In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The swollen Songhua River is
posing a threat to a million people in the areas along the river
in the section near Harbin, capital of northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province and a major heavy industrial center and
grain production base.
</P>
<P>
The water at the Harbin Hydrology Station rose to a level of
118.93 m. and 8,120 cu.m. per second by 8:00 a.m. today, 0.8
m. higher than the danger mark.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that the third flood crest will arrive at
the Jiangqiao Hydrology Station tomorrow, when the water level
there is expected to be 142.5 m. and the flow rate 15,000 cu.m. a
second. The first crest passed through the city on July 22, and
the second on August 9.
</P>
<P>
The 26-km-long embankment of the Songhua River in Harbin's
urban area is intact and life in the city is normal. Harbin has a
population of nine million.
</P>
<P>
Navigation on the river has been suspended, but residents are
still walking, playing chess, or selling goods along the river as
usual.
</P>
<P>
At an emergency meeting yesterday, the city government asked 9
counties and cities along the river to remain on alert, and local
people are being urged to prepare flood-control materials, and
officials to get people to fortify river embankments and
reservoirs and dangerous sections, and to arrange rescue teams.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 2.5 million people are patroling the river bank,
according to one government official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
