<HEADLINE> Cambodian King Willing to Play Conciliatory Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian King Norodom
Sihanouk said he would be pleased to play a conciliatory role if
asked to do so by two or three of the major political parties,
opposition party leader Sam Rainsy said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The King also said he would be prepared to preside over
a 'Siem Reap Informal Meeting' if requested by two or three of the
major parties," Sam Rainsy said.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, president of Sam Rainsy Party (SRP), and his
five-member delegation Wednesday met with King Sihanouk in Siem
Reap to discuss ways for forming the new government after the
general election.
</P>
<P>
Rainsy described the two-hour meeting as a "private
conversation."
</P>
<P>
"The king congratulated the National Assembly Members-elect of
the SRP and said he considers the SRP as now having a role in the
government of Cambodia," Rainsy continued.
</P>
<P>
The king said it was advisable for the parties to have
dialogue, according to Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
Rainsy said to the King that the proposed Siem Reap Informal
Meeting could be a way to break a possible deadlock and that the
SRP will consider this suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Second Prime Minister Hun Sen reacted immediately to
the king's suggestion, saying that he was ready to take part in
the meeting at any time.
</P>
<P>
Prince Norodom Ranariddh and his Funcinpec Party has not yet
made any comment on the king's suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec and the SRP, the second and third largest political
parties, had been boycotting the results of the election, claiming
that there were fraud and irregularities in the voting and ballot
counting and that the seat-allocation formula changed by the
National Election Committee (NEC) was illegal.
</P>
<P>
With the NEC no longer considering election complaints, Sam
Rainsy's only legal option is to take his grievances to the
Constitutional Council. But Sam Rainsy doubts the Council will be
fair.
</P>
<P>
In response, he has planned a series of demonstrations in the
country to show public support for his refusal to accept the
election results. The first demonstration is scheduled for this
weekend in the capital, but it has not yet been arranged in
details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
