<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stable Growth In China's Iron And Steel Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China's iron and steel output
continued to rise a great deal in the first half of this year,
according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Steel production grew 6 percent from the same 1997 period to
55.2 million tons during the first half, with pig iron output up
7.2 percent to 57.2 million tons, and rolled steel up 6.9 percent
to 49.6 million tons.
</P>
<P>
China has 46 iron and steel enterprises with annual output of
more than 500,000 tons each, which accounted for 85.6 percent of
the country's total steel production in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's Baoshan Iron and Steel Group, one of the country's
leaders, produced 4.42 million tons of steel, 4.39 million tons of
pig iron, and 3.27 million tons of rolled steel in the first half.
</P>
<P>
The country produced 36 million tons of continuously-cast steel
billets during the period, a 16.4 percent rise from the same 1997
period, while open-hearth steel was down to 2.9 million tons,
accounting for 5.27 percent of the country's total steel output.
</P>
<P>
Economists say that demand for iron and steel is expected to
increase by the end of the year, because of increased
infrastructure construction and use of technology in enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
