<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices languished at
lows unseen in decade on Singapore Stock Market Wednesday amid
lingering fears over regional currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index (STII) dropped
12.16 points to 995.77 points to record a fresh 10-year low, and
closed below the much-eyed 1,000-point support-level . The STII
hit an intra-day low of 992.43 before recovering to 995.77 despite
a recovery in regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
The slump came after the STII fell by 31.34 points to close at a
ten-year low of 1,007.93 points Tuesday. The last time the index
closed lower than this was on December 5, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Market was seized by jitters over the weakness of the Japanese
yen and investors feared a re-enactment of last year's Asian
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the sharp fall on Wall Street overnight as
well as concerns over the region's economy and expectations of
poor corporate results had cast a pall on the market.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is there is very little buying interest," said a
dealer with a European-based investment bank.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was 143.86 million shares valued at 232.53
million Singapore dollars (about 133.63 million U.S. dollars).
Losers outstripped gainers by 145 to 133 while 310 counters
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Frt Links was the most active stock of the day as it registered
a turnover of 14.95 million units. It was followed by DBS Land
that had 8.02 million stocks traded. TAC 200 was next with 5.79
million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
MISC F topped the gainers of the day as it edged up 35 cents to
close at 1.70 Singapore dollars. Robinson rose by 20 cents to
finish at 4.20 Singapore dollars. Shangri was up 18 cents to end
at 2.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser of the day
as it lost 60 cents to close at 17.70 Singapore dollars. Thai Pr
slid by 55 cents to finish at 2.30 U.S. dollars. SIA 200 ebbed by
40 cents to end at 5.45 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
