<HEADLINE> Chinese State Councilor Meets With Chairman Of U.S.'s Amway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese State Councilor Wu Yi,
in a meeting here today with Stephen Van Andel, chairman of U.S.'s
Amway, congratulated the company on its successful conversion from
direct sales to shop sales and said she appreciates Amway's
understanding of China's decision to forbid all direct sales.
</P>
<P>
She said that President Bill Clinton's China visit helped
promote the Sino-U.S. relations and the United States has changed
the "Most Favored Nation" status into "Normal Trade Relations",
but the annual status review still leaves U.S. businessmen with a
feeling of instability.
</P>
<P>
She explained that China is still in a period of transition
from a planned to a market economy and its laws and regulations
are not perfect, the people in direct sales are not of very high
quality, and consumers are not very mature either, so direct sales
are not appropriate in China.
</P>
<P>
Van Andel said Amway is still full of confidence about the
China market and will observe the law anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
Amway (China) Co., Ltd. was etablished in 1992 as a Sino-U.S.
equity joint-venture, with total investment of 100 million
U.S. dollars and 80 million registered capital.
</P>
<P>
Its parent company, Amway, was set up in 1959 in the United
States and now does business in at least 80 countries and regions,
where it sells its products through direct sales.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
