<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Military Rules Out Regional Armies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian senior army officer
has criticized the call for regional military forces in the
country under a new political arrangement, saying: "the
consequences of such a gesture can be very grave."
</P>
<P>
"There can never be regional armies in Nigeria, whatever the
situation," said Nigeria's Chief of Defense Staff Air Vice
Marshall Al-Amin Daggash, who came to the current position early
last month.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was not in order, he said Tuesday, adding it
would be unrealistic to think of regional forces, the Post
Express reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces have recognized their subordinate role to the
civilian authorities as they prepare to hand over in May next
year to an elected government, Daggash told visiting members of
the African Refugees Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The military has ruled Nigeria for more than two decades since
the country won its independence from the British colonial master
in October 1960. A May 29, 1999 deadline for the military to
quit power was set by the current military regime three weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, two of Nigeria's three major ethnic groups,
the Igbo and Yoruba which have been fighting for a power shift
from the northern Hausa people, called in separate deliberations
for the establishment of regional armies.
</P>
<P>
It was the only way of addressing the "marginalization"
presently going on in the military, they argued.
</P>
<P>
The call, according to the Igbos, followed the non-appointment
of an officer from the Igbo-speaking areas into any of the
command positions in the military during the re-alignment of its
officers recently.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters has condemned the calls, saying they
are politically motivated and promotions in the military are
purely by merit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
