<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Export Growth Shows Negative Trend: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Secretary to the Union
Ministry of Industry T.R. Prasad said Wednesday that India's
industrial exports have registered a negative growth rate of eight
percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a national seminar on "administrative reforms to
help liberalize procedures" in Hyderabad city, 1,453 km southeast
of New Delhi, Prasad said, "Indian industry is losing on
competition in the international market and there is a need for
correction."
</P>
<P>
The country's industrial export grew by 22 percent during
1995-96 and by two percent in 1996-97 and 1997-98, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need to create a competitive environment for Indian
industry to flourish besides improving the infrastructure
facilities," he said, adding "We cannot expect Indian industry to
compete globally with the present infrastructure deficiency."
</P>
<P>
The reform process had to be accelerated in the country, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
