<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breached Dike in Jiujiang Cemented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- After five days of strenuous
effort, a 60-meter-long breach in the Yangtze River embankment at
Jiujiang section in east China's Jiangxi Province was cemented
completely this afternoon, declared the provincial deputy governor
Huang Zhiquan on the scene.
</P>
<P>
The make-shift dike is some 1.2 meters higher than the Yangtze
water level, which has dropped to 22.74 m now, 0.03 m lower than
the same time on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 soldiers and civilians are still working to further
fortify the newly-built section of embankments, which has been
built in a shape of a trapezium, 4 meters wide at the top, 18
meters at the bottom, and nearly 100 meters long, sources said.
</P>
<P>
At 2:10 this afternoon, soldiers began to position iron
frameworks into the last 2-meter gap, and dump sandbags to link up
the opening.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to repair the damage started shortly after a section of
the concrete embankment was breached around 1:10 pm on Friday,
four kilometers west of downtown. Rescuers sank eight boats and
dumped truckloads of rocks, rice, soybeans and whatever else was
at hand into the breach because of a severe shortage of filling
materials. By now, more than 20,000 tons of stone, or 9,400 cubic
meters, have been used in the effort.
</P>
<P>
However, technical problems, a lack of expertise and inadequate
equipment slowed the work.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, a team of army experts has been summoned from Hebei
Province in north China to help Jiujiang plug the breach. And the
army experts decided to hammer in dozens of steel pipes in four
rows into the breached dyke, while a 90-meter cofferdam has been
built next to the breach to slow the flow of water.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers successfully put up a framework by striking hundreds
of steel pipes into the breach, and sandbags and other filling
materials were added to the framework to plug the breach
completely.
</P>
<P>
"The previous dumping of boats and other materials has slowed
down the water flow by one-third and laid a good foundation for
our operation," said an expert.
</P>
<P>
People have built a dike 5,000 meters long at a spot two
kilometers from the breach, and a second dike 3,000 meters long
and four kilometers away from the first, to prevent a four-sq-km
flooded area in the western part of the city from expanding
further.
</P>
<P>
"With the completion of these two in-city dikes, I'm now quite
at ease," said Chen Zhenglai, deputy director of the Municipal
Water Conservation Bureau and head of the flood control
headquarters for the city's urban districts.
</P>
<P>
The flooded western part of the city, stranded in one-m-deep
water, includes a new industrial zone and home to 18 communities
and eight enterprises and institutions, with a population of
35,810.
</P>
<P>
Since the breach occurred, some 10,000 people affected by
floodwaters have been resettled in their relatives' houses or
factory buildings. There have been no reported casualties at the
breach so far, according to Governor Shu Shengyou and some
on-the-spot witnesses.
</P>
<P>
"Tents are not necessary for these relocated people, because we
have enough space for them to stay," said Chen, adding that
supplies of running water, electricity and daily necessities have
been adequate in the city.
</P>
<P>
The city proper of Jiujiang, an industrial center and tourist
attraction on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, has an
urban population of 500,000 and covers an area of about 30 sq km.
</P>
</TEXT>
