<HEADLINE> Surging Floodwaters Hit Qiqihar in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Rising water levels in the
mainstream of the Nenjiang River resulting from torrential
rainfall are threatening levees protecting Qiqihar, an industrial
base in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The water level at Qiqihar hit 149.18 meters by 11:00 am on
Wednesday, up 46 cm on the Tuesday level, with the 107.69 meter
level at Tongmeng accompanied by a flow rate of 11,500
cu.m./second.
</P>
<P>
Floodwaters have weakened and seriously threatened the
integrity of extensive sections of levees protecting the city and
water rising as much as one meter above the surface of the No.2
Highway Bridge has forced closure of the transportation artery.
</P>
<P>
Over 200,000 local residents and soldiers are maintaining a
constant vigil along levees, and residents in Gannan, a county town
threatened by rising water levels in a nearby reservoir, are being
evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Crews are also working frantically to repair damaged sections
of the Siping-Qiqihar and Harbin-Manzhouli railways.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers have evacuated the majority of over 6,000 local
residents in Tailai County, and operations continue to move the
over 1,000 remaining residents to safety.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
