<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
higher Wednesday in Sydney following remarks by Japanese officials
that the Japanese central bank would move to support the Japanese
yen when necessary.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished trade at 59.85 U.S. cents from
59.53 U.S. cents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The currency had opened trade at two-month lows after the
Japanese yen slumped to fresh eight-year lows against the U.S.
dollar overnight.
</P>
<P>
However, a turnaround in both the yen and the Australian dollar
was affected by comments by Haruhiko Kuroda, a bureaucrat from
Japan's ministry of finance, suggesting the Bank of Japan was
ready to jump into the fray.
</P>
<P>
Kuroda said the Japanese government was concerned about any
deviation from fundamentals that the yen would take, and would not
hesitate to act if it deemed it necessary.
</P>
<P>
A nervous market, which had propelled the U.S. dollar to 147.61
yen Tuesday night, sold it off just as quickly, dropping two yen.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was changing hands at 87.34 Japanese yen
from 87.79 yen.
</P>
<P>
Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's vice minister for international
affairs, added to the intervention rumor, saying "if it is
necessary, we will intervene."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also buying 1.0640 German marks from
1.0622 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
