<HEADLINE> China's Human Rights Position Improves: Australian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said here Wednesday China's human rights position
had improved in the past 14 months, the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister's remark came a day after China and
Australia concluded their second round of human rights dialogue
Tuesday in Canberra.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly in the last year there has been an improvement, even
if it hasn't been everything that any of us would like," the
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Proof of improvement was that China had committed to signing
two international human rights conventions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is now a growth of dialogue between China and other
countries on human rights issues rather than just the sort of
accusatory diplomacy we had in the past. So that is a constructive
thing," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister defended Australia's human rights dialogue
with China against criticism that it ignored major issues such as
China's one child policy, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the talks had agreed on a wide-ranging Joint
Program of Cooperation on strengthening human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
