<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French government has received thousands of petitions
from members of some ultra-conservative groups and catholic groups
which call for the abandoning of a project to legalize contract
between homosexual and heterosexual partners, which will be
discussed by the National Assembly on October 9.
</P>
<P>
-- The Congolese who are disappointed with the rule of President
Laurent-Desire Kabila are waiting for the outcome of the fighting in
the western part of the country between government forces and the
rebels. Opportunistic, many Congolese are also seeking alliance in
Rwanda and Uganda in case of a change of government in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- France continued to suffocate under strong heat on Tuesday.
For the fourth day consecutive, big French cities registered the
peak of pollution. The highest temperature attained 40 degrees
centigrade in the cities of Yvonne and Nievre.
</P>
<P>
-- The stock markets worldwide continued to suffer from the purge
on Tuesday with all the stock indexes falling in the United States,
Europe, Japan and Russia. The Japanese yen fell to its lowest in
eight years on Tuesday, while Japan's new prime minister seemed to
have used up all the cartridges for reviving the country's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
