<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Accelerates Rebuilding Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) said on
Wednesday that the firm is accelerating its rebuilding process as
the negative effects of the strike launched by its employees last
month are waning.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, PAL said that it envisions a more efficient
and reliable but reduced domestic and international airline
service with a manpower complement of 8,578, including 200 pilots,
and a young fleet of 21 jet planes averaging three years in age.
</P>
<P>
The airline management is confident that PAL still remains the
leader in the national air transport business despite its reduced
size because the company is way ahead of its closest competitors
in many areas.
</P>
<P>
The press release said PAL's closest competitor has only nine
airplanes compared with PAL's 25 state-of-the-art jets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PAL, the country's flag carrier, has retained 19
stations for domestic and seven for international after it
implemented a major downsizing program in June.
</P>
<P>
The confidence of the public in PAL is coming back as the
airlines' passenger load remained fairly high despite labor
problems and the lean season, the airlines said.
</P>
<P>
PAL, which is now under the receivership of the Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC), continues coordinating with the
government agency to assure the success of a plan to rehabilitate
the national carrier.
</P>
<P>
The company, having been wracked by labor and financial
problems, is now run by an interim receivership committee. This
committee is finalizing a rehabilitation plan detailing the
strategies necessary to resuscitate the company.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which is scheduled to be submitted to the SEC by the
end of October, also spells out how the company's 2 billion U.S.
dollars debt will be restructured, and its schedule of payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
