<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Survey Informal Sector of Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is
expected to soon embark on a national survey of the informal
sector of the economy for better planning, a leading national
newspaper, This Day, reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The exercise would enable the government to document relevant
issues in the informal sector as they integrate or interfere with
national planning objectives, it said.
</P>
<P>
The informal sector, which is described to have been
responsible for the survival of the Nigerian economy, is made up
of al the parallel activities that complement the functions of
the official or formal sector.
</P>
<P>
It is in recognition of this fact that the Federal Office of
Statistics (FOS) is embarking on the survey of the informal
sector by September so as to have adequate information on it,
said FOS Director-General Oladejo Ajayi.
</P>
<P>
According to him, there is in most cases a parallel market to
every genuine market that exists. But the activities of the
informal sector are not recorded and so cannot be measured or
regulated.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely believed that non-official business
activities worth billions of Naira are executed annually at
border areas but the money is not recorded because there are
people who do not use the bank as a means of saving money.
</P>
<P>
In this case, the government in its economic planning does not
have adequate knowledge of the prosperous border trade.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the balance of payment accounts and
all macro-economic indicators, which are part of the country's
international transactions, may not also be correct because most
Nigerians' international transactions do not come in through the
country's ports as a result of complications.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the total output of the Nigerian economy is given
by the sum of consumption, investment, net exports and imports.
</P>
<P>
However, in line with the FOS official's views that most
business activities have parallel ones, total consumption,
investment, net exports and imports can never be known, the total
output of the Nigerian economy cannot be determined correctly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
