<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Floods Affect China's Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The flooding on China's Yangtze
River over the past two weeks has caused great losses of life and
property and economists say that it could lower this year's
economic growth rate by 0.5 percentage points and cause 200
billion yuan in losses.
</P>
<P>
Water levels in the river are still well above the warning line
and it will be another two weeks before they fall below it. The
total direct losses will surpass 200 billion yuan, economists predict.
</P>
<P>
There was flooding on the Yellow and Nenjiang rivers as well,
and by the beginning of August, 240 million people and 21.5
million ha of farmland had been affected.
</P>
<P>
Early rice yields were down, and autumn grain yields are
expected to be affected, according to Wang Yuexin, a State
Statistics Bureau official. However, he would not say by how much
since the flooding is not over.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Agriculture official says that it will be
difficult to reach this year's target of 490 billion kilograms of
grain and predicts a growth rate for agricultural value-added
products at around 3 percent, with the 4-percent goal difficult to
reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
