<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 08:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Buy 28 Military Choppers from U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Navy has decided to
buy a total of 28 Sea Hawk helicopters from the United States
before 2010, Turkey's Daily News reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of eight helicopters made by the Sikorsky
Company worth 205 million U.S. dollars will be delivered by 2001,
senior Turkish defense sources, who declined to be named, were
quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
An advance on the helicopters, accounting for 15 to 20 percent
of the total cost which has yet to be disclosed, was paid by
Turkey in June, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Sea Hawk choppers are armed with airborne survival
equipment, data and voice communication systems and advanced
weapons control systems.
</P>
<P>
But the Hellfire air-to-surface missiles, which are initially
part of the Sea Hawk, are not included in the deal and will be
discussed in separate negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkey is considering buying Sikorsky-made S-70
Black Hawk helicopters. But the number is unknown.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Export-Import Bank is expected to finance the Black
Hawk deal as proposed by the company.
</P>
<P>
Turkey itself can only meet 20 percent of its demand for
weapons and military equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
