<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The floods also slowed industrial growth. Latest figures for
July show a growth rate of 7.6 percent, 0.3 percentage points
lower than in June. The State Statistics Bureau attributed the
slowdown partially to the floods and said that some firms have had
to be closed.
</P>
<P>
The effect was two-sided. The floods delayed some
infrastructure projects and weakened consumer spending in rural
areas, but the large-scale home rebuilding activity after the
floods is expected to stimulate consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
Signs indicate more spending on infrastructure in the second
half, and Xiang Huaicheng, Minister of Finance, told a conference
recently that the country will have "more active" policies to spur
the economy.
</P>
<P>
The floods also changed government opinion about construction
of flood-control facilities. The State Development Planning
Commission has decided recently to spend more in this area than the
previous increase of 1.7 billion yuan at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
One economist told the "China Economic Times" recently that if
there is a new driving force for economic development, the floods
will be a good thing in a sense. 
</P>
