<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Calls for Setting Up Modernized Ocean Patrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Du Bilan, a member of the
National People's Congress' Environmental and Resource Protection
Committee (ERPC), says that China needs a more efficient and
modernized ocean law-enforcement system, similar to the United
States Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
Du told a conference on the Marine Environment Protection Law
that China, with its 10,000 km of coastline and 3 million
sq.km. of sea, has serious marine pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
She said that, in 1984, another country was drilling illegally
in Chinese territorial waters, but that China failed to notice at
the time.
</P>
<P>
China did set up a Marine Environmental Law-enforcement Team in
1985, with branches in Qingdao, Shanghai, and Guangzhou, to
investigate cases of marine pollution. Customs, transportation,
and fishery officers also patrol the ocean.
</P>
<P>
Du says that lack of cooperation between these teams has
greatly effected law enforcement and their equipment also needs
modernization.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
