<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's trade deficit for the first seven months
totaled 3.47 billion U.S. dollars, a 26 percent drop from 4.67
billion a year earlier, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit dropped to 460 million dollar in July after
exports reached 1.87 million while commodities imports stood at
2.33 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Trade between Israel and Oman totaled less than
half a million dollars last year, Israeli newspaper Haaretz quoted
official Omani figures as reporting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Oman and Qatar are the only two Gulf countries which have
commercial representations in Israel. Oman reported that Israeli
products made up 0.009 percent of its total imports, Haaretz said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The federation of commercial software manufacturers
has made tangible progress in the Arab world in combating computer
virus and the copying of computer programs, Wednesday's Egyptian
daily "Alam Al Yom" reported.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the total losses caused by software piracy in the
Middle East dropped to 92.116 million dollars in 1997, compared
with 137.669 million dollars recorded in 1996.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- The Bahraini government is endeavoring to increase
its electricity production by completing the 280-megawatt "Heed"
station during the year 1999.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the station have already started, and upon
its completion, available electric power in the country will reach
1,480 megawatts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
