<HEADLINE> Lesotho Army Surrounds Palace to Disperse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho Army
surrounded King Letsie III's palace in Maseru Wednesday morning
in a bid to disperse protesters who have gathered there since
last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Basotho National Party President Evaristus
Sekhonyana said army chief Lieutenant-colonel Makhula Motakeng
had instructed the protesters to disperse in a radio broadcast
Tuesday evening, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"Early on Wednesday morning the army began surrounding the
royal palace. Another tank, inside the palace, is facing toward
the gate in the direction of the crowd," Sekhonyana said.
</P>
<P>
He said opposition parties, who are protesting against the May
election which they claim was rigged in favor of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy, had asked South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki to give the assurance that the army would
not be introduced into the dispute.
</P>
<P>
"Mbeki told us that he hoped the army would not be used. We
are (exerting) political pressure on a political issue and I do
not understand why the army is being used."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki was in Lesotho Monday to broker a deal between
government and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the establishment of a South African-sponsored
committee to probe opposition allegations seemed to have failed
to appease protesters, who are demanding an intervention of the
king. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
