<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Pakistan to Seek Release of Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran again called on Pakistan to
help seek the release of its 11 diplomats reportedly held by the
Afghan Taliban forces, the official news agency IRNA reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi told IRNA that
Islamabad had earlier assured Tehran the safety of its diplomats
in Mazari-e-Sharif before the Taliban stormed into the city.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban forces, believed to have been supported by
Pakistan, took captive Saturday the 11 Iranian diplomats and a
correspondent after their conquer of Mazari-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The fall of the city, the main stronghold of the opposition
Northern Alliance, marked a major victory for the Taliban, which
has won control of most of Afghanistan and imposed a strict form
of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
Iran, which supports the opposition headed by President
Burhanuddin Rabbani, has repeatedly urged Pakistan to secure the
safety of its diplomats.
</P>
<P>
But the Pakistani embassy in Tehran said on Tuesday that
Islamabad "cannot be held responsible for developments in
Afghanistan and Pakistan has nothing whatsoever to do with the
internal developments in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The Taliban force issued a statement on Tuesday that it is not
holding any Iranians in Mazari-e-Sharif. The diplomats have fled
the Consulate General in the city when its militia arrived, it
added.
</P>
<P>
And the Taliban said the missing Iranians would not be
recognized as diplomats and they, if arrested, would be tried and
punished as agents of a hostile government.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said evidences and documents available indicated that
Taliban's claim that the Iranian Consulate General was empty when
its militia forced an entry "is a mere lie."
</P>
<P>
Iran's special envoy for Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi
Tuesday rejected the Taliban's claim, terming it as violating
international laws and principles.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Taliban can not shirk its responsibility
for the safety of the Iranian diplomats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
