<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Urged to Ratify Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado
on Wednesday urged anew the ratification of the Visiting Forces
Agreement (VFA), saying the Philippines needs regular joint
military exercises with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Do we need these exercises? I believe it is so," Mercado told
a forum held here.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the importance of the 48-year old
Philippine-U.S. Mutual Defense Treaty (MDT) signed by the two
countries in 1951.
</P>
<P>
The VFA, which was signed earlier this year by the two
countries, has yet to be ratified by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The VFA will enable American and Filipino soldiers to test
their effectiveness in the event of war under the 1951 MDT,
Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will also give Philippine soldiers an opportunity
to familiarize new weapons used by the Americans.
</P>
<P>
Annual Philippine-U.S. military exercises held under the MDT
have been suspended since late 1996 after the Philippines began to
negotiate with the U.S. a new agreement on the status of visiting
foreign forces.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of the VFA, war games cannot be held in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Americans are asking the Philippine government to ratify
the VFA before their troops can conduct big military exercises.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Senate has been strongly opposed to the VFA,
which many senators said favors the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
