<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Spies Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A Beijing court today convicted
four Taiwan people for espionage, and sentenced one defendant to
four years' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The four defendants worked for the Taiwan Military Intelligence
Bureau, according to the verdict handed down by the Beijing No.1
Intermediate People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Kou Jianming, the defendant sentenced to four years'
imprisonment, and the three other defendants -- Chen Shaoyu, Han
Yueting and Zhou Changming -- illegally entered the mainland and
engaged in political, economic and military espionage between June
of 1993 and March of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Chen, Han and Zhou were exempted from criminal punishment for
performing meritorious services to atone for their crimes.
</P>
<P>
Kou was sentenced to prison and deprived of all political
rights for two years in accordance with China's Criminal Law.
</P>
<P>
The four Taiwan people carried out espionage activities
while ostensibly working for the "Civil Exchange Association of
China" and under the cover of commercial activities, according to
the verdict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
