<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Threaten to March on Kinshasa Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The rebels in parts of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have threatened that they will
march on the capital Kinshasa in the coming days, rebels
commanders told the Rwanda News Agency (RNA).
</P>
<P>
Commander Sylvain Mbuki, the spokesman of the rebel forces,
claimed Tuesday that the rebellion has not met much resistance in
the towns they have captured, quoted by RNA.
</P>
<P>
Mbuki was among the senior commanders of the 10th battalion
that initiated the revolt in Goma, east DRC, a week ago, RNA
said, in a dispatch to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
On the military situation, Mbuki claimed that the rebels are
fighting in Matadi in Bas Congo province which he alleged might
fall any time.
</P>
<P>
"We are heading toward Kinshasa," Mbuki declared.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, government spokesman in Kinshasa said that after a
series of setbacks at the hands of rebellious troops in the east
and west, loyalist troops are turning the tables on the enemy
at present.
</P>
<P>
The DRC state radio reported Tuesday that 18 fleeing Rwandan
soldiers had been killed in a gun battle with loyalist troops at
a village outside Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
DRC Information Minister Didier Mumengi was quoted as saying
Tuesday that in the west of the vast central African country, in
the province of Bas Congo wedged between Congo and Angola, rebel
troops had been surrounded and would be "pushed toward the sea."
</P>
<P>
He said government troops in the east are preparing an assault
on Bukavu. "Our forces are moving eastwards" after taking the
Kahuzi Biega game park, 50 km north of Bukavu, he said.
</P>
<P>
The DRC has been accusing Rwanda and Uganda of backing the
Congolese Banyamulenge Tutsis in the fighting that has spread
from the east to the west of the country. The Banyamulenge
rebelled on August 2.
</P>
<P>
At the Kinshasa airport after a regional meeting in Zimbabwe
Tuesday, President Laurent Kabila said agencies operating in the
east had witnessed the involvement of Rwandan forces.
</P>
<P>
A special committee of four heads of state has been set up at
the Zimbabwean meeting to probe the alleged involvement of other
armies. A separate committee of the Organization of African
Unity has been holding talks with Kabila's ministers as well as
officials in Rwanda, Uganda and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
