<HEADLINE> N.Z. Official Calls for Buying Domestics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Deputy Prime
Minister and Treasurer Winston Peters plans a national tour to
relaunch a "Buy New Zealand-Made" campaign in the country.
</P>
<P>
If the price and quality are right, "then we owe it to
ourselves and our fellow New Zealanders to buy New Zealand-made
goods," an Auckland-based newspaper Wednesday quoted Peters as
saying in his recent trip to Dunedin, a city on New Zealand's
South Island.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Herald also quoted the deputy prime minister as
saying "We should not fall into the trap of thinking imported
items are better simply because they are foreign."
</P>
<P>
New Zealanders should be proud about wearing and using New
Zealand-made products, Peters said.
</P>
<P>
"We should be vigilant and question why an imported item is
used in preference to something made here by our fellow countrymen
and women.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing unhealthy about investing in our patriotism.
It is one further form of savings in the nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Peters said that he thinks "there is a role for a wise
government in supporting exporters in business."
</P>
<P>
"It is not about picking winners but rewarding winners in a
sound export-based economy," he stressed. 
</P>
