<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Problem for Chinese Universities (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Lu Jiaming, a teacher from
Shanghai International Studies University, was far more than
surprised when he unfolded the files of a group of students.
</P>
<P>
Lu, who came to Beijing to enroll freshmen for his university,
found that these candidates are all females who passed this year's
university entrance examinations.
</P>
<P>
He wrote a letter to the Beijing Municipal Enrollment Office,
asking to reduce the number of students his university had
originally planned to recruit.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that to solely enroll female students is really an
embarrassment to him and his university. An excess of female
students has already created many problems in university
management, he said, and for the growth of female students
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that a survey has shown that male students only account
for 32 percent of the university's total, and there are only "a
few" male students in some specialties, causing problems in
teaching and management.
</P>
<P>
This also is a problem for Beijing Foreign Studies
University. At present, male students only account for 25 percent
of its total enrollment. Among the university's newly recruited
112 students, only 25 are males.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Youth Daily, female graduates from
some foreign studies universities usually feel nervous when they
meet with males in business talks, because they have few chances
to talk with males while they are in university.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Problem for Chinese Universities (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In some foreign studies universities, students have to "borrow"
male students to hold dances, and it is usually a headache for
university authorities to arrange dormitories for such a small
number of male students. These universities also miss the chance
to take part in team sports, because they do not have enough male
students.
</P>
<P>
The same problem also exists in some arts universities. A
teacher from People's University, who asked to remain anonymous,
said that female students accounted for 46.2 percent of the
university's total freshmen in 1996, 48.1 percent in 1997 and the
rate is expected to exceed 50 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, only 687 out of the 2,657 students who have passed
the bottom enrollment marks set by local institutes of arts are
males.
</P>
<P>
A female university president, who also wished not to be named,
said that, apart from the fact that females are having more and
more chances to go to school, the basic reason for their increase
as university students lies in the school education and
examinations.
</P>
<P>
She added that choosing students solely according to marks and
examinations based on memory is favorable to female students.
</P>
<P>
Many teachers attributed the change in enrollment to the
education system based examinations. They said such an education
system is actually a way to eliminate male students, who are
active in thinking and have broader interests.
</P>
<P>
An expert said that the essence of the question is not whether
female students are good or not in studying, but the key is that
the increase in the number of female students has reflected
shortcomings in teaching methods and ways for choosing talented
people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Ocean Environment Protection Needed: Lawmaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) - Zou Jiahua, the vice-chairman of
the National People's Congress Standing Committee, says that the
government needs to do more to protect the ocean environment from
severe pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese legislature sent teams to Hainan, Liaoning and
Shandong provinces in May and June of this year to see how the law
was working there, and local legislatures in 8 other coastal
provinces and cities have been ordered to check the situation in
areas under their jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
The ocean environment is becoming more contaminated and the
situation in offshore areas is especially worrisome and is
deteriorating, Zou said after receiving reports from the
inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
China has 18,000 km of coastline and 3 million sq.km. of ocean,
which is useful for sustained growth, Zou said, and officials
should do better exploring and protecting it. Over 70 percent of
China's coastal waters are polluted and below national standards.
</P>
<P>
From 1980 to 1997, there were 280 red tides in China's
territorial waters. The government needs to increase control of
major coastal projects, offshore oil exploration, dumping of
waste, and drainage, and close factories that threaten the ocean
environment, in accordance with the law, Zou said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
