<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Industrial Production Index Down 3.5 pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Reflecting the slowdown in
industrial activities, Malaysia's industrial production index
(IPI) dropped 3.5 percent in the first half of this year to 145.4
from 150.7 in the same period last year, according to official
statistics released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IPI fell 3.7 percent to 140.6 in June this year compared
with 146.1 in May, and compared with June 1997, the IPI declined
by 6 percent, according to the Statistics Department which
released the index for June.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed the January-June decline to a 5.6
percent drop in the index of the manufacturing division to 159.6,
where 17 out of a total of 23 major groups registered lower
indices in January-June this year compared with the indices for
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The major groups registered lower indices during the period
under review included transport and equipment, footwear except
vulcanized or moulded rubber or plastic footwear, iron and steel
basic industries, machinery except electrical, glass and glass
products, and non-metallic mineral products.
</P>
<P>
The remaining six major groups recorded higher indices for the
period January-June 1998 compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The groups included plastic products, rubber products,
professional and scientific and measuring and controlling
equipment, tobacco manufactures, wearing apparel except footwear,
electrical machinery, apparatus, appliances and supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
