<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lead Pollution in Dhaka Highest in World: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The level of lead pollution in air
in Dhaka city during November to January is the highest in the
world, the national news agency BSS reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The lead pollution in the air reaches its highest level of 463
nanograms (one nanogram is one billionth of a gram) per cubic
meter in the city during the dry season during November to
January, the news agency quoted a recent study of the Bangladesh
Atomic Energy Commission as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Mexico city was previously considered as the city with the
highest level of air pollution where the level of concentration of
lead is 383 nanograms per cubic meter, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The use of petrol containing lead is primarily responsible for
lead pollution in the air of Dhaka city, which threatens public
health.
</P>
<P>
The lead particles spreading in the air with the petrol smoke
are so fine that the upper part of human respiratory organs is not
capable of preventing them from being inhaled into the body, a
senior scientific officer of the commission said.
</P>
<P>
Then they enter into the lungs, mix up with blood during its
circulation, and accumulate in the teeth and bones of the human
body. At a certain stage, the deposited lead causes serious damage
to the human body, the scientific officer said.
</P>
<P>
The lead concentration in Dhaka's air varies according to
season, from 463 nanograms per cubic meter to 160 nanograms per
cubic meter during the monsoon season, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
