<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Produce High Heat Duty Fire Clay Bricks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will produce fire clay
bricks which can withstand over 1,250 degrees of heat for the
country's industries.
</P>
<P>
A fire clay brick factory of state-run Myanma Ceramic
Industries (MCI) was opened here Tuesday to produce 900 tons of
such high heat duty fire clay bricks annually, the official
newspaper New Light of Myanmar reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The factory, which cost over 3.55 million U.S. dollars, was
built in May 1997 to produce import substitute goods for
industries in the country to reduce foreign exchange expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar imported similar high heat duty fire clay bricks
annually for industries including cement plants.
</P>
<P>
The country's annual requirement of the bricks is over 1,200
tons for national industries including cement plants, steel mills,
 glassware, glass and ceramic factories and others.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country is producing low heat duty fire clay
bricks which can withstand up to 1,250 degrees of heat for saw
mills, rice mills, sugar mills, furnaces of small-scale steel
smelters and factory furnaces which transmit less heat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Industrial Activity to Stay Sluggish in 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- India's industrial activity is
expected to remain sluggish during fiscal year 1998-99 (April 1
1998-March 31 1999) with no turnaround likely in the second
quarter because of high lending rates, said the National Council
for Applied Economic Research (NCAER), here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its latest economic forecast, the independent think-tank
said that the economy, gripped by poor growth and low business
confidence, may not see a recovery in the second quarter too,
especially in the backdrop of economic sanctions imposed on India
by the United States following India's nuclear tests in mid May
this year.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates and probable rupee depreciation are
unlikely to allow upswing in credit and imports to continue and
that this would impede manufacturing activity.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the government's massive borrowing program would put
pressure on domestic financial resources leading to a rise in
interest rates and this coupled with higher cost of foreign loans
would hinder fresh investment, NCAER said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
