<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Denies Albanian Accuses of Chopper Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior Yugoslav military
officer denied Tuesday Albania's accuses on the Yugoslav Air
Force's helicopter invasion, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
reported.
</P>
<P>
The officer said the Albanian accuses were intended to avoid
their responsibility for training and arming terrorists and
sending them to Yugoslavia. He added that Albania wanted to give
the impression to the world that it is under dire threat from
Yugoslavia on the eve of the NATO military exercises, which will
be held in Albania next week.
</P>
<P>
If something goes wrong during the exercises, they would to be
able to shift the blame to Yugoslavia, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian government claimed that Yugoslav Air Force
helicopters invaded Albanian territorial sky on August 8 and 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
