<HEADLINE> Trust Fund Set Up in Myanmar Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A trust fund of 16.4 million
Kyats (2.7 million U.S. dollars) has been set up at the Yangon
General Hospital here, the largest and the oldest one in Myanmar,
to buy expensive and potent medicines for poor patients.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the fund is a meritorious deed as it will
help save the lives of the poor, Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt,
first secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and Development
Council, was quoted on Wednesday by the official newspaper The New
Light of Myanmar as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government is spending nearly 3 billion Kyats (500 million
dollars) annually for the health sector, using separate funds for
health care services in border areas, disclosed Khin Nyunt, who is
also Chairman of the National Health Committee, at the fund
raising ceremony Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A cost-sharing health care system between the government and
the private sector has been introduced, he noted, pointing out
that Myanmar physicians, who are skilled practitioners, have the
ability to cure various diseases in the country, depending on the
availability of sufficient advanced equipment and potent
medicines.
</P>
<P>
The cost-sharing health care system, which was introduced
recently on account of the limited ability of the government to
bear all the national health expenditures alone, also called for
attending to the poor.
</P>
<P>
Up to March this year, there were 734 hospitals with more than
14,000 doctors in Myanmar, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has worked out a five-year national health plan for
1996-2001 which includes six broad programs and 50 detailed
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
