<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> La Nina Important Cause of China's Flooding, Scientist Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences, Chao Jiping, says that El Nino's opposite, La Nina,
has been a major cause of south China's floods.
</P>
<P>
Chao said that subtropical high pressure systems generally move
northward to north China in July with considerable strength, which
would end the flood season in the Yangtze River Valley.
</P>
<P>
"However, the appearance of the La Nina phenomenon has weakened
the strength of the subtropical high pressure and forced the main
body of the pressure to move southward to 18 degrees north
latitude from its position at 30 degrees north latitude on July
10."
</P>
<P>
Chao said that under such a condition, with the help of the
ample water vapor coming from the south, south China's Yangtze
River Valley and Dongting and Poyang lakes suffered another heavy
rains this year, which have caused serious floods.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that the background of this year's
floods in the country is surprisingly similar with that in 1954
when serious flooding occurred.
</P>
<P>
An El Nino weather phenomena appeared in 1953 followed by a La
Nina in 1954. This year's La Nina also followed last year's El
Nino, which was the strongest this century.
</P>
<P>
"The strength of the La Nina this time seems no less than that
of the El Nino in 1997," Chao said.
</P>
<P>
The La Nina phenomenon, the opposite of El Nino, means
colder-than-normal surface temperatures in the Pacific Ocean, and
greatly affects global weather patterns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exports Fall 4.1 Percent On Sluggish Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports in the first
half of the year plunged 4.1 percent in dollar term due to
sluggish demand in Asia, a government press release obtained
Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports in the first six months were worth 26.93
billion U.S. dollars, down 4.1 percent compared to the same period
last year, while import value fell sharply to 21.43 billion, or
38.1 percent, resulting in a trade surplus of 5.49 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the major export markets of Thailand, the United States
increased 13.3 percent, the European Union 12.1 percent, Africa
28.5 percent and Australia 8.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, major markets in Asia recorded a sharp decrease,
with South Korea plunging 43.9 percent, followed by ASEAN
countries, down 22.5 percent, and Japan 16.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Export items increasing in value are rice, canned sea food,
computer, electronic products, automobile and parts and rubber
products.
</P>
<P>
Main imported products, namely fuel, capital, raw materials,
consumer products, automobiles and others, all recorded sharp
plunges of more than 30 percent, with automobiles even dropped 89
percent.
</P>
<P>
Thailand had been ambitious to achieve a 7.1 percent increase
in exports at the beginning of this year but had to lower the
target to 1 to 2 percent later since the baht's devaluation did
not boost exports as the government expected.
</P>
<P>
Experts even said the country's exports in this year will be
down two percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrival of Soldiers to Mend Dike Puts Residents at Ease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- While thousands of soldiers are
working hard to plug a breach in the city embankment on the
Yangtze River in Jiujiang, a city in Jiangxi Province, local
residents say they are no longer anxious and worried about their
future.
</P>
<P>
Residents of this east China city were scared in the first
hours after the dike burst at 1:30 p.m. on Aug. 7, but they said
calm prevailed shortly afterward because of timely and effective
help from the local government and the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
"I was cutting a birthday cake for my 9-year-old son when I
heard people fleeing for their lives in the streets," said Pan
Jingping, 35, who works at a local dairy.
</P>
<P>
Pan brought her son hurriedly to the New Spring Primary School,
a temporary shelter for more than 70 flood victims, from their
houses several hundred meters from the breached dike.
</P>
<P>
Pan returned to her house at 7 p.m., six hours after the
breach, to move furniture to upper floors. "Once I was worried if
my things could be stolen in my absence, but later I felt at ease
because police were patroling the area," she said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shenghua, in her 30s, arrived at the school two days
after the breach occurred. She heard someone calling people to
flee. "I didn't want to leave my house, because I wanted to keep
an eye on my fish ponds," she said.
</P>
<P>
But she asked neighbors to bicycle her 89-year-old
mother-in-law, Chen Jinbao, and two children to the primary school
which is an hour's walk from the breached dike.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's husband, a transient laborer in another city, forced
her to leave home, but her father-in-law refused to go with them
and stayed on the third floor.
</P>
<P>
"There is no danger in my house," she said, adding that the
water was only a half-meter deep there.
</P>
<P>
Cao Guohua, 45, a handicapped tailor, said she was worried
during the first days of the breach. "But after I heard that
soldiers had been sent to repair the dike, I'm no longer worried,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Cao continues her business at her house in the daytime and
sleeps at the primary school.
</P>
<P>
The school provides meals to those who did not bring cooking
utensils. "The local government says we will be financed later,
but for the time-being, we have to manage it by ourselves," said
Cao Yuxia, the schoolmaster.
</P>
<P>
In the downtown streets, brisk businesses are going on
everywhere, with prices a little higher than normal. "It is
understandable as we now have more people than ever in our city,"
said a local resident.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of civilians and soldiers from other parts of
the country have rushed to the rescue these days. Many of them are
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
Food prices jumped on the first day of the breached dike, with
inflation ranging from 50 percent to 120 percent. They began to
fall on the second day. "There are plenty of supplies of food and
vegetables, so the prices cannot go up too much," said Wang
Fangqun, who works at a vegetable shop.
</P>
<P>
Business is quite good for Qi Longxing, a taxi driver. "My son
is preparing for marriage, therefore I must work hard," he
said. Many of his fares came from journalists, tourists and others
who came to help mend the breach.
</P>
<P>
Many local residents have voluntarily sent food and drinks to
soldiers and civilians who are working on the dike. In addition to
the breached dike, two secondary dikes have been built to protect
water plants and power stations as well as the downtown.
</P>
<P>
"Everything here is normal," said a local journalist, "and you
can see it from the booming restaurant business and so many people
are strolling in the streets.
</P>
<P>
"But the only luxury goods are boats, since a large number of
people are working on the breached dike or visiting those working
on it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
