<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher Death Rate Blamed for Speed Limit Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The increase in highway
speed limits from 88 to 104 and 120 kilometers per hour in most of
U.S. states translates into an increase in higher death rate, said
a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fatalities in California rose by 16 percent, including an
increase of 22 percent on 104 kph highways and 12 percent on those
highways with an increase to 162 kph, said the study done by the
August issue of the Annals of Emergency Medicine
</P>
<P>
A preliminary assessment indicated that states with the higher
speed limits experienced a 9-percent increase in interstate
fatalities, or 350 more deaths, than historical trends predicted,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The National Maximum Speed limit (NMSL) enacted in the 1970s to
conserve oil by setting highway speed limits at 88 kph, was
overturned by new legislation at the end of 1995. Eleven states
quickly moved to increase their speed limits on certain highways,
21 gradually increased speed limits over a matter of months, and
19 states made no changes.
</P>
<P>
Those states that immediately increased their speed limit had
the most pronounced increase in traffic fatalities, while there
was no statistically meaningful increase in the other states,
concluded the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Fall Under 13 Dollars Per Barrel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices fell below
13 U.S. dollars a barrel Tuesday, the first time in seven weeks on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, reports here said.
</P>
<P>
September crude fell 29 cents to 12.76 dollars per barrel. The
price of heating oil was down 0.42 cents to 34.02 cents a gallon,
while the September price of unleaded gasoline dropped 0.64 cents
to 40.01 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
Market sources say the major reason behind the decrease is the
fear that demand from Asia will not rebound strongly enough to
alleviate the world's depressed oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The American Petroleum Institute reported that U.S. oil
supplies rose last week. 
</P>
