<HEADLINE> Italian Official Warns of Mafia Threat to Euro Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Mafia is planning to
take advantage of the new single European currency, the euro, to
launder money, threatening to cause havoc in the financial and
monetary system, Palermo Mayor Leoluca Orlando warned in the
German daily Die Welt on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The financial branch of organized crime inevitably operates
where it is the most convenient and its increasing mobility is
taking it to Germany where the movement of money is the fastest",
the mayor warned in the article.
</P>
<P>
Orlando said that his city, Palermo, has changed from the Mafia
capital to the anti-Mafia capital and was willing to offer its
experiences to prevent the change to the euro becoming "a gigantic
washing machine."
</P>
<P>
He said that German police and the judiciary seemed to have
understood the critical role which Palermo could play.
</P>
<P>
Orlando, also a member of the European Parliament, said he had
submitted four anti-Mafia law drafts to the parliament, and three
had already been approved.
</P>
<P>
"This law package is a fundamental weapon for fighting the
spread of Mafia racketeering and the criminals' designs on the
Euro," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
