<HEADLINE> Beijing to Upgrade Power Grid for More Power Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will conduct a massive
upgrade of its power grid to reduce the blackouts and short
circuits in Beijing's power supply, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The renovation will allow the city to supply 1.5 million
apartments with at least 6,000 kilowatts by the year 2000, said
Tang Songhan, a manager with the Beijing's Power Supply Co..
</P>
<P>
Tang said the new network will be able to handle increasing
power demands as more residents buy large appliances like air
conditioners, microwave ovens and vacuum cleaners, that use a lot
of electricity.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government, the utility, and consumers will share
the cost of rewiring buildings built prior to 1995.
</P>
<P>
Electricity has been in short supply in Beijing for the last
two decades. Blown fuses were a common occurrence.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's power shortage was relieved after a tow-year
upgrade started in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that Beijing has enough power to supply the city's
growing needs but the power grid still can not handle the added
current.
</P>
<P>
The electric utility company is working to attract more users
and sell more of its products, for industrial electrical demand
has dropped since many state-owned enterprises shrunk after
reforms started in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Currently, industry uses a little more than half of the total
electrical supply, down from 60 percent in the early 1990s.

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
