<HEADLINE> Peru to Create Commission Against Asian Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian businessmen have suggested
the government create a technical commission to protect the
national textile industry against Asian imports.
</P>
<P>
Peru's textile and design sectors have been affected by a flood
of Asian products.
</P>
<P>
National Industry Society Chairman Eduardo Farah said Tuesday
that the commission should take measures to defend local industry
against unfair competition which was caused by Asian products.
</P>
<P>
He said that Peruvian products could not compete with goods
from some Asian countries where currencies have been devalued and
the sale prices were below production costs.
</P>
<P>
George Scholfield, chairman of the Textile Committee, said that
Colombia, Venezuela, Mexico, Chile, Argentina and Brazil were
going to increase tariffs by 100 to 200 percent on Asian products
in order to protect their own textile industries.
</P>
<P>
He said the imports of Asian goods in Peru amounted to 14
million U.S. dollars in the first quarter of this year, five
million dollars more than the same period last year. 
