<BODY>
<HEADLINE> La Niqa Important Cause of China's Flooding, Scientist Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences, Chao Jiping, says that El Niqo's opposite, La Niqa,
has been a major cause of south China's floods.
</P>
<P>
Chao said that subtropical high pressure systems generally move
northward to north China in July with considerable strength, which
would end the flood season in the Yangtze River Valley.
</P>
<P>
"However, the appearance of the La Niqa phenomenon has weakened
the strength of the subtropical high pressure and forced the main
body of the pressure to move southward to 18 degrees north
latitude from its position at 30 degrees north latitude on July
10."
</P>
<P>
Chao said that under such a condition, with the help of the
ample water vapor coming from the south, south China's Yangtze
River Valley and Dongting and Poyang lakes suffered another heavy
rains this year, which have caused serious floods.
</P>
<P>
Historical records show that the background of this year's
floods in the country is surprisingly similar to that in 1954
when serious flooding occurred.
</P>
<P>
An El Niqo weather phenomena appeared in 1953 followed by a La
Niqa in 1954. This year's La Niqa also followed last year's El
Niqo, which was the strongest this century.
</P>
<P>
"The strength of the La Niqa this time seems no less than that
of the El Niqo in 1997," Chao said.
</P>
<P>
The La Niqa phenomenon, the opposite of El Niqo, means
colder-than-normal surface temperatures in the Pacific Ocean, and
greatly affects global weather patterns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
