<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China City Reduces Noise Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Noise control measures have been
adopted to scale down noise in Yantai, a coastal city in East
China's Shandong Province, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
No car is allowed to blow in the urban districts and no sirens
are allowed there. Outside broadcasts of music and advertisements
have also been forbidden in commercial areas since June 1.
</P>
<P>
About 98 per cent of the hourly 3,000 vehicles on the main
avenue abided by the ban and traffic noise was reduced.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, Yantai has found and stopped more than 100
noise-pollution sources.
</P>
<P>
The average decibel level in the street has fallen by 10 points
since June.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Yantai Environmental Protection Bureau said
that the birds and cicadas sound louder than ever in the city.
</P>
<P>
The city has also banned the use of firecrackers during
holidays, weddings and funerals three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Several cities in the province, including Qingdao, Jinan and
Weihai, have car horn bans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
