<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jakarta Military Commander Vows to Secure Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Jakarta Military Commander Maj.
Gen. Djadja Suparman Monday night pledged to deploy thousands of
military personnel to help secure the capital ahead of next
Monday's celebration of the anniversary of Indonesia's
independence.
</P>
<P>
Suparman made the pledge in a meeting with representatives of
non-governmental organizations amid rumors of renewed mass
rioting.
</P>
<P>
"All personnel stationed in Jakarta will be involved. If the
city police chief asks us for support, we are ready," he was
quoted by the local press Tuesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Suparman reiterated that he would cooperate closely with city
police chief Maj. Gen. Noegroho Djajoesman, who is in charge of
security in the city.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-five thousand military personnel and 17,000 police
officers are stationed in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Rumors have been circulating over the past few weeks that a
fresh wave of rioting would erupt a few days ahead of the August
17 celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Suparman called on the city's residents not to believe the
rumors, some of which have been spread on pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the capital's security forces held a parade of 1,500
police and military personnel to help convince the public that
they were ready to handle any further outbreaks of unrest.
</P>
<P>
Suparman also urged certain parties not to mobilize the masses
or stage rallies that could lead to unrest. Those ignored the
request would face legal sanctions, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"We must uphold the law. The city police chief has made
repeated calls for this. Let's unite to pursue this," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
