<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee Li Peng called the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters Tuesday evening, inquiring about the flooding
situation in the Nenjiang River in in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
He urged local people to fight the flooding according to the
anti-flood law and further reinforce river embankments to
protect the major cities along the river such as Harbin.
</P>
<P>
-- A senior official of China's central bank yesterday ruled
out again the possibility of any devaluation of Renminbi yuan.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need for the yuan to devalue and it will not
devalue," Liu Mingkang, deputy governor of the People's Bank of
China, said at a press conference in Beijing yesterday morning.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier and Head of the State Flood Control and Drought
Relief Headquarters Wen Jiabao has urged provinces along the
Yangtze River to make strenuous efforts to protect the Yangtze
embankments and win an overall victory over the floods, the worst
since 1931.
</P>
<P>
The anti-flood chief made this remark Tuesday while presiding
over a meeting in Jingzhou city in central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
-- China's total industrial output added value reached 1,108.1
billion yuan (133.5 billion US dollars), up 7.8 percent over the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- In spite of severe floods in South and Northeast China, the
incidence of epidemic diseases has stayed low, thanks to proper
and prompt prevention methods, the Ministry of Health said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, no outbreak of epidemic diseases has
been reported nationwide so far and the small-scale presence of
some water-borne communicable diseases, mostly leptospirosis and
epidemic haemorrhagic fever, in some flooded areas has been kept
under control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
