<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Freeze Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Banks in the Philippines have
decided to freeze lending and deposit rates for at least a week
despite the latest round of increases in overnight interest rates
by the country's central bank, a newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deogracias Vistan, president of the Bankers Association of the
Philippines (BAP), was quoted by the Philippine Journal as telling
reporters that the banks would hold off such increases for at
least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank on Tuesday hiked anew its overnight borrowing
rate by another three percentage points, from the present 15
percent to 18 percent, in a matter of 24 hours in a bid to quell
speculation against the Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
"For as long as the central bank limits the interest rate
increases to overnight rates only and the speculation (on the
peso) does not last indefinitely, or over two weeks, the banks
will not change their rates," Vistan was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Present bank lending rates are pegged to the 91-day Treasury
Bill rate of around 14.1 percent plus 1.5 percentage points up to
six percentage points as spread to cover relevant expenses,
according to Vistan.
</P>
<P>
But if the central bank changes its term interest rate, the BAP
will impose changes in both deposit and lending rates to reflect
the new equation, Vistan explained.
</P>
<P>
Deposit rates, especially time deposit rates, will have to be
adjusted appropriately if the above parameters no longer hold
because by then the banks will have to scramble to retain
customers through attractive deposit rates, Vistan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
