<HEADLINE> Richina Pacific Pins Hope on Its China Subsidiary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Richina Pacific expected
significant sales growth from its Shanghai Richina Leather
subsidiary, Chief Executive Tony Caughey was quoted as saying here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to New Zealand Press Association (NZPA), after months
of negotiation, Richina's business partner, Shanghai Leather
Corporation, has handed over a 40 percent stake in the business in
return for Richina buying its plant for 2.5 million NZ dollars
(about 1.3 million U.S. dollars) and taking out a 29-year lease of
its land and buildings. As a result, the Shanghai Leather
Corporation will own the lease and hold a five percent
non-participating interest in the business.
</P>
<P>
NZPA quoted Caughey as saying that having achieved its first
pre-interest operating profits in May, in line with expectations,
the leather business was generating higher sales than last year.
</P>
<P>
Sales for the six months to June 30 were 18 million NZ dollars
(about 9.2 million U.S. dollars), compared with 3.9 million NZ
dollars (about two million US dollars) in the previous
corresponding period, and a new contract with a United States
retailer was expected to raise sale volumes "significantly",
Caughey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
