<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000-year-old Frescoes In World's Loftiest Ancient Kingdom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered wall paintings dating back 1,000 years in a temple
belonging to the Guge Regime, the "Kingdom of Heaven", located
nearly 5,000 m. above the sea level in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
They say that the frescoes are the earliest ever found of the
regime that ruled the northwestern part of Tibet from the 10th to
the 17th century. The regime was Buddhist and known for its
exquisite wall paintings in a great number of grottos and the
Mtho-ldin Temple.
</P>
<P>
The earliest paintings were found in two pagodas at either end
of the Kharsa Hall, which are among the oldest structures in
Mtho-ldin.
</P>
<P>
An archaeological expedition found them earlier this year. The
scholars believe that the paintings are the earliest and
best-preserved ever found at Ngari, in western Tibet, although
they are not certain what they depict. They also found the remains
of Buddhist sutras in Tibetan, statues, bows and arrows, iron
armor, and building materials.
</P>
<P>
Ngari is where scholars discovered 21 grottos scattered across
a 3,000-sq.km. area in the Zanda Earth Forest. They say that this
is the largest group of caves ever found in the country.
</P>
<P>
At Zanda they also found cliff paintings describing the daily
life of early people there. The findings will contribute to the
study of Tibetan Buddhism, architecture, sculpture, painting, and
the history of Ngari, according to Gyal Yang, the head of the
regional Cultural Relics Administration, who says they plan to
excavate relics and maintain ancient buildings, using 7 million
yuan from the central and local governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
