<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Employment Provided in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The number of employees in
various sectors in Myanmar totaled 18.36 million in the 1997-98
fiscal year which ended in March, up from 17.96 million in the
previous year, indicating a growth in employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
An annual official report on the country's financial, economic
and social conditions revealed that the agricultural sector was
the largest contributor to the total employment amongst the
productive sectors, accounting for 11.51 million or 62.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
The processing and manufacturing sector employed 1.66 million
or 9.07 percent and the remaining productive sectors comprising
energy, mining, electric power and construction sectors employed
570,000 or 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Services sector such as transport and communications, social
services, administration and other services engaged 1.98 million
or 10.79 percent and the trade sector 1.78 million or 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are being made to fully utilize the increasing labor
force and to promote productive efficiency through increased
supply of skilled personnel along with creation of job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
According to another official Selected Monthly Economic
Indicators, a total of 16,657 persons got employed through the
State Labor Department out of 142,070 registered in the capital of
Yangon alone in 1997-98, 4,151 more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's gross domestic product (GDP) achieved a 4.6 percent
increase in 1997-98, in which the productive sector rose by 4.3
percent, the services sector by 7.4 percent and the trade sector
by 3.2 percent as compared with 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Of the productive sector, agriculture, the mainstay of the
country's economy, contributed the largest share or 35 percent of
the total GDP, followed by processing and manufacturing as the
second largest contributor which represented 9.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
