<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 00:30 GMT, August 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States has temporarily closed a
half-dozen embassies for security adjustments following last
week's bombings at its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, a senior
U.S. official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We're not shutting embassies down in a permanent sense. We are
not leaving. We are taking, in effect, a brief timeout in order to
make security adjustments that are necessary to be responsive to a
threat," Assistant Secretary of State Patrick Kennedy
said.(US-Embassy Bombings-Embassy Closure )
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The U.S. dollar rose to an eight-year high against
the Japanese yen Tuesday as investors continue to dump yen for
safer currencies.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 147.35
Japanese yen, up from 146.15 late Monday. During the day, the
dollar reached 147.61 yen, a level not seen since August 20, 1990,
when the dollar hit 147.96 yen.(New York-yen Tumbling )
</P>
