<HEADLINE> Luxemburgo Becomes Brazil New Soccer Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Vanderley Luxemburgo was
given the tough job on Tuesday to coach the Brazilian national
soccer squad after the Sanba dancers failed to win the fifth
World Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
Luxemburgo, who twice coached his Brazilian club to league
titles, succeeds Mario Zagallo who was removed after Brazil lost
3-0 to France in the World Cup title game last month.
</P>
<P>
"I am very satisfied," Luxemburgo said, "To be part of the
national team is the objective of any soccer professional, be he
a coach or a player."
</P>
<P>
However, it is premature to discuss plans for the team until
personnel in the national soccer federation is set and
"priorities are established", he said.
</P>
<P>
Luxemburgo, 46, coach of first-place Corinthians, will
continue his job in the team until the end of the national
championships in December.
</P>
<P>
The first players for the new national team are expected to be
named in September.
</P>
<P>
Started his coaching career in 1983, Luxemburgo has coached 14
teams, including two in Saudi Arabia. He led Palmeiras to the
national championship in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
Being a lackluster player in his 11-year career from 1971 to
1982, Luxemburgo gained national attention in 1990 as coach of
Bragantino, an obscure team that won the Sao Paulo state
championship.
</P>
<P>
After coaching Flamengo in 1995, he returned to Palmeiras. He
coached Santos in 1997 and this year joined Corinthians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
