<HEADLINE> Roundup:Afghan Taliban Claim More Gains on Battle Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- As intense fighting continues
in war-ravaged Afghanistan, the Taliban militia claimed Tuesday
evening another strategic gain with the fall of Taloqan, capital
of Takhar province, to the Taliban forces.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia also claimed more military gains in other
provinces controlled by the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
After loosing its stronghold of the strategic northern Afghan
town, Mazar-i-Sharif, the fall of Taloqan is certainly another
major setback for the beleaguered Northern Alliance which groups
forces of former Afghan defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood,
Uzbek-ethnic warlord Rashid Dostum and Shiite Hezb-e Wahdat.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Wali Naeemi, a Taliban representative based in
Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's North West Frontier province, told
Xinhua Tuesday evening that the Taliban forces have captured 80
percent of the area of Takhar province including the provincial
capital of Taloqan.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that forces of the Northern Alliance have now fled
to adjoining Badakhshan province after the fall of Taloqan to the
Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Naeemi also claimed that the Taliban fighters have also
captured Charakeen falling between Mazar-i-Sharif and central
Bamyan province, Taighan Shamand in Bamyan province, Talabarfag in
Baghlan province and Kohisafi in Kepisa province.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces captured the districts after negotiations
with local population and on their "wish", said the Taliban
representative, adding that majority of the rival forces left the
areas while some surrendered voluntarily to the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban do not want fighting any more, they want
settlement of disputes with leaders of the Northern Alliance
through negotiations with local authorities and residents," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces made a strategic gain on the Afghan battle
field last week when they captured Mazar-i-Sharif, headquarters of
the Northern Alliance, giving a worst blow to the opponents.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban's military gains have caused serious
concerns to the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports the Tajikistan government, with the
help of 25,000 Russian troops stationed in the country, has beefed
up the security measures and started reinforcing its borders with
Afghanistan Tuesday to guard against any spill over of the turmoil
in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, the Kazakhstan government said
that leaders of four former Soviet republics in central Asia are
considering joint action to guard against any Taliban incursion
into their territories.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iran, followed by Turkey, has already urged the
United Nations and Pakistan to contain the Taliban militia from
harming the civilians in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that with the fall of Mazar-i-Sharif, the
Taliban are now occupying almost 90 percent of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe the U.N., the Organization of Islamic
Countries and Afghan neighbors should all speed up their efforts
to find a framework for the solution of the Afghan issue as there
are fears that the conflict in Afghanistan may enter a more bloody
phase if concerted efforts are not made at this stage to bring the
warring factions to the negotiating table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
