<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celtic Bonus Row Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Celtic have its bonus row
resolved after managing director Fergus McCann took 50,000 pounds
(81,590 U.S. dollars) from his players and donated to a
children's charity on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The players at Parkhead had been involved in a stand-off with
McCann over the amount he was willing to pay if they won the home
leg of their Champions' League qualifier with Croatia Zagreb on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Marc Rieper, Henrik Larsson and Jackie McNamara made their
feelings known by failing to turn up for a team photocall on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
But it then emerged that all the players were united in the
protest.
</P>
<P>
Club captain Tom Boyd said: "The course of events yesterday
were the culmination of many months of trying to resolve the
situation in an amicable way for both the players and the club.
</P>
<P>
"It appears that a solution was not possible, and therefore in
consultation with all the squad members, the three players took
this stance of non-cooperation."
</P>
<P>
McCann is sticking by his original bonus offer, but he said
the issue had now been settled after a 50,000 pound sum was
awarded to Yorkhill Hospital.
</P>
<P>
"I want to show the players what is important in life - some
people don't even have a salary or a life to look forward to,"
said McCann.
</P>
<P>
McCann has accused his players, many of whom earn more than
10,000 pounds per week, of trying to blackmail the club, which
had offered the biggest in bonus in its history.
</P>
<P>
"I have spoken to the players and they are not very happy
about what we've done," said McCann.
</P>
<P>
"But we felt it was appropriate action. They should get a
reality check. We have gone beyond our contractual obligations to
them with regard to bonuses, they have not fulfilled theirs.
</P>
<P>
"A bonus payment in not an entitlement. In football, there are
clubs who can be blackmailed, but Celtic is not one of them."
</P>
<P>
McCann said that he had spoken to other British club chairmen
over the last few days and said what Celtic are offering for one
tie is more than one English club has put on the table for winni
ng the UEFA Cup outright.
</P>
<P>
More than 60,000 fans will fill Parkhead on Wednesday hoping
that the row will not affect the performance of Jozef Venglos's
side.
</P>
<P>
Celtic, who won the European Cup in 1967, have reached the
continent's premier competietion for the first time in a decade
and the supporters are desperate to see their team reclaim their
place among the top bracket in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Venglos revealed that Scotland World Cup midfielder Craig
Burley could yet play, despite doubts over his fitness after
damaging knee ligaments in a friendly with Liverpool last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Croatia Zagreb are confident they can succeed where they
failed last year when they lost to Newcastle at this stage on the
away goals rule. Striker Mark Viduka said: "The British style
suits us down to the ground. It is Celtic who should be quaking
in their boots." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
