<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drugs Checks May be Delayed by Lack of Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- England Football Association's
plan to step up random drug testing for soccer stars might be
delayed by a row over funding.
</P>
<P>
After Ron Atkinson revealed last weekend that drug abuse was
widespread in the game, Lancaster Gate announced plans to double
the number of tests they carry out at training grounds around the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a book entitled "A Different Ball Game", the former Arsenal
manager alleges that Premiership players take to the pitch every
weekend "with cocaine, cannabis and all sorts of funny tablets
buzzing around their system".
</P>
<P>
His claims have once again reopened the debate about drugs in
sport. That debate reached new heights this summer after doping
scandals involving athletics and cycling's Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
Despite statistics which show that the problem of drugs in
soccer is receding - only three tests in 500 turned out to be
positive last season - Atkinson's comments suggest the FA's
approach could be falling short of the mark.
</P>
<P>
FA officials disclosed their intention to widen the program
but the UK Sports Council's anti-doping unit, the organisation
responsible for the independent monitoring of drug testing, still
believes that the game lacks the commitment to get to grips with
the issue.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations are unlikely to be put in place until next
season after the UKSC told the FA that they would not help
finance the new procedures.
</P>
<P>
Michelle Verroken, director of ethics and anti-doping at the
UKSC, said: "Increasing the FA's program would mean an expansion
of the UKSC's responsibilities but we have not got any money to
cover that."
</P>
<P>
"Their plans can only be seen as a stepping stone and they are
going to have to look again at how they are approaching this," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The FA spend around 500,000 pounds (some 820,000 US dollars)
on its drug testing and education program of which 50,000 pounds
is provided by the UKSC. The new program will cost the FA an
extra 60,000 pounds a season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Backs to Top 10 by Beating Kiefer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Andre Agassi of the United
States showed his determination and power to regain his former
world number one position by beating Nicolas Kiefer of Germany in
the 2.45 million U.S. dollars ATP Championship in Mason, Ohio of
the United States on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He won four straight points to force a tiebreaker after
falling behind 30-0 in game 12 of the second set, then won
through over Kiefer 4-6, 7-6 (7-3), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Agassi climbed back in the top 10 of the
world rankings for the first time since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think you show up to any tournament and play your
best tennis in the first round," Agassi said. "You've just got to
get through the days when you're not feeling the greatest."
</P>
<P>
The former world No. 1 player was ranked a distance No. 141 in
last November. "It's nice to feel competitive again," said
Agassi, who is currently ranked ninth in the world.
</P>
<P>
Kiefer, who is 25th in the ATP rankings, never had played
Agassi before. "It was a good chance to beat him. I played him
very aggressive. I see that I can beat him."
</P>
<P>
Two seeded players of the tournament were beaten today. Thomas
Muster of Austria beat 11th seed Tim Henman of Britain 6-4, 7-5,
and Wayne Ferreira of South Africa downed 15th seed Felix
Mantilla of Spain 7-6 (7-5), 7-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genetically-Modified Foods Prohibited in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Genetically-modified foods
will not
be allowed to be sold in New Zealand unless they have passed
rigorous
assessments of safety on a case-by-case basis, New Zealand
Minister for
Agriculture and International Trade Lockwood Smith announced here
Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Smith was commenting after an experimental trial in Britain
suggested
that rats fed with genetically-modified potatoes suffered slightly

stunted growth and increased vulnerability to disease.
</P>
<P>
The results of the experimental trial in Britain are being
further
analyzed in order to assess their real significance and New
Zealand
authorities would take a close interest in seeing the data and
examining
it thoroughly, Smith said in his announcement.
</P>
<P>
Under the standard established by the Australia-New Zealand
Food
Authority (ANZFA), sales of genetically-modified foods will be
prohibited
in New Zealand unless they have passed a rigorous assessment of
safety,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The ANZFA process will provide the highest level of safety
assurance," he stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
