<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Musicians Popularize Folk Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese musicians want to
develop folk music and make it more popular to protect the unusual
Chinese cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on traditional Chinese music in the capital of
northeast China's Jilin Province they expressed a concern about
the possibility that there will be no people to follow folk music,
because of popular music and songs.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese have been producing their own music for 8,000 or
9,000 years. But now, in many cities, children learn to play
pianos and violins instead of traditional Chinese instruments.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shiju, an associate professor in the music department of
Northeast Teachers University, says that musicians should be
responsible for popularizing folk music and introducing more
people to folk music.
</P>
<P>
Some musicians say that more attention should be paid to the
quality of folk music and improving the variety of traditional
Chinese music.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
