<HEADLINE> Polish Teams Have Mixed Night at UEFA Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Wisla Krakow of Poland
celebrated their late escape from FIFA's threatened ban on all
Polish international soccer with a 5-1 victory over Trabzonsor of
Turkey in the first leg of their second qualifying round tie at
UEFA Cup on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tomasz Kowalik led the win with a hat-trick. Other two goals
for the winners were scored by Daniel Dubicki and Bogdan Zajac
respectively.
</P>
<P>
But there was disappointment in the capital as Polonia Warsaw
went down 1-0 to visiting Dynamo Moscow with the lone goal from
Rolan Gusiev at the 54th minute.
</P>
<P>
Former European champions Crvena Zvezda (Red Star Belgrade)
needed a 90th minute penalty by Perica Ognjenovic to beat Russian
side Rotor Volgorad 2-1 while in Sweden IFK Gothenburg edged Fene
rbahce of Turkey by the same score.
</P>
<P>
Rangers, in the UEFA Cup after nine years fighting for the
European Cup, beat PAOK Salonika 2-0 in Glasgow with second half
goals by Andrei Kanchelskis and Rod Wallace but fellow Scots
Kilmarnock went down 2-0 to Sigma Olomouc in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
It was a bad night for Belgium as 1983 winners Anderlecht lost
3-1 at Croatia's Osijek while Germinal Ekeren slumped to a 4-1
home defeat at the hands of Swiss team Servette.
</P>
<P>
Ferencvaros of Hungary were cruising to a 4-0 home victory
over AEK Athens but were stunned as the Greeks scored twice in
injury to keep the tie alive.
</P>
<P>
Czechs Slavia Prague, however, made no late slips as they
hammered neighbouring Slovaks Inter Bratislava 4-0.
</P>
<P>
There were also celebrations in Cyprus as Omonia Nicosia beat
Austrian heavyweights Rapid Vienna 3-1. 
</P>
