<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Suffer Another Bad Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- European stocks markets closed
sharply down Tuesday after Wall Street's afternoon slide, despite
news of the merger of BP and Amoco, two of the world's biggest oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
British shares slumped, triggering the second largest fall in
London's blue-chip share index since the stock market crash of
1987.
</P>
<P>
News of the world's biggest ever industrial merger between
energy giants British Petroleum and Amoco failed to cheer the
plunging market. The FTSE 100 index closed 154.8 points lower at a
seven-month low of 5,432.8.
</P>
<P>
A BBC report quoted Jeremy Batstone, head of research at
NatWest Stockbrokers, as describing the market "busy contemplating
suicide as it stared down the barrel of a gun."
</P>
<P>
"If it hadn't been for the BP and Amoco tie-up and its brief
soothing effect, the market would have fallen further," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier gains among a number of oil stocks were eroded in the
wake of profit-taking. Investors panicked at plummeting shares in
Japanese stocks amid fears that the Asian meltdown was far from
over, according to market analysts.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the German market did not escape hefty losses on
Wall Street, closing almost 4 percent weaker.
</P>
<P>
Dealers talked about the prospect of the Dax testing the
psychologically and technically significant 5,000 points level
soon, as the floor-traded DAX index closed 3.80 percent weaker at
5,268.40 points, while the electronic Xetra DAX finished 3.2
percent lower at 5,285.78 points today.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks ended down more than 2 percent after being
pummelled by what analysts called confusion over Indonesia's debt
repayment and Wall Street's fall on fears of currency devaluations
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip Cac-40 index ended down 93.47 points, or 2.37
percent, at 3,845.98 but above its session low.
</P>
<P>
At one point, the index slumped to 3,786.19, its lowest level
since late April, but it steadied slightly later, and climbed back
above 3,800 before the close. 
</P>
</TEXT>
