<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Banks Reject Employees' Condition of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan bank employers Tuesday
to abandon their seven-day strike and resume work following
Friday's bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
The 52-member Banks of the Kenya Bankers Association (KBA)
maintained that the employers' collective decision to sack the
striking employees was final.
</P>
<P>
The best the employers can do at this stage is to peruse
application letters from the sacked workers without any guarantee
of employment, said KBA Executive Officer Baphael Chubi.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Union of Commercial, Food and Allied Workers
(KUCFAW) said Monday that the strikers are ready to reconsider
industrial action, in view of Friday's bombing which killed at
least 224 people and injured nearly 5,000.
</P>
<P>
KUCFAW gave four conditions, which KBA rejected Tuesday "as
they (the striking workers) ceased to be our own."
</P>
<P>
"Our decision, unfortunate decision so to speak, still remains
intact and if they (the striking workers) want jobs, they are
free to reapply," said Chubi.
</P>
<P>
KUCFAW had wanted the employers to withdraw all the dismissal
letters already served on members. The union also wanted workers
to be allowed to resume work unconditionally and without
victimization.
</P>
<P>
It also asked the Kenyan government to give a firm commitment
to implementing the decision of the tripartite committee on the
contentious tax and the fringe benefits tax.
</P>
<P>
The fourth condition was that the employers should abandon the
requirement that the workers reapply for their jobs.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a bad decision, only that it comes when it is too
late to do anything other than allow them a chance for
reapplication," Chubi replyed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bankers went on strike last Monday in protest against the
government's plan to tax interest-free or low-interest loans
available to bank staff.
</P>
<P>
They have since been dismissed en-masse by the bank employers,
under the umbrella KBA.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the Cooperative Bank of Kenya, which is
placed fourth in the Kenyan banking industry, was extensively
damaged in the bomb attack early Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
