<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Government, Opposition Squabble over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A government report about the
safety of nuclear energy production sparked a heated debate
between the German government and opposition parties on Tuesday
about whether it is necessary to shut down the country's nuclear
power plants.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear safety report presented by German Environmental
Minister Angela Merkel on Tuesday showed that Germany had
registered 2030 cases of technical defaults in nuclear power
plants over the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
Among those defaults, however, there were only two cases that
were of acute nature that need to be reported publicly immediately
and 51 cases belonging to the category of less serious technical
defaults that need to be reported within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Merkel told reporters in Bonn that the report showed that by
international standards, German nuclear power plants had an
"excellent safety level".
</P>
<P>
She also reiterated the government position that there was no
need for Germany to get rid of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD), however, saw
in the government report a proof that great risks are involved in
the production of nuclear energy and that the possibility of a big
accident still cannot be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
The environmental speaker of the SPD, Michael Mueller,
suggested on Tuesday that Germany gradually shut down nuclear
power plants in about ten years.
</P>
<P>
Juergen Trittin, a leader of the German ecologist Greens party,
on Tuesday repeated his criticism of the government for a recent
nuclear scandal during which excessive contamination had been
found in a number of German nuclear waste shipments to a
reprocessing plant in France.
</P>
<P>
The Greens has been calling for a quit from nuclear energy as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the opposition demand, Merkel noted that an important
reason for Germany to retain nuclear power plants was that Germany
could gain more experience in nuclear technology and then could
help enhance international safety standards.
</P>
<P>
There are now 19 nuclear power plants in operation in Germany
which produce about one third of the annual energy supply for the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
