<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks plunged today,
sending the Dow industrials down 112 points to 8,462.85, nearly
900 points below the record of 9,337.97, set on July 17.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indicators also slid among large amount of sell
orders.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 18.42 to 1,064.72, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 48.64 to 1,790.56.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 770.94 million
shares as against 572.64 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index slid 7.77 to 537.95, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 20.53 to 659.27.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 11.04 to
400.60.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen tumbled to an eight-year low against the
dollar today as a new assessment of the Japanese economy gave no
encouraging signals.
</P>
<P>
Also affecting the market were the reports today from the U.S.
Labor Department on the first drop in U.S. worker productivity in
more than three years and from federal court officials of record
personal bankruptcy filings by Americans.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo stock prices fell for the seventh consecutive trading day,
losing 1.4 percent and setting off another wave of selling on other
battered Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, the Hang Seng Index in Hong Kong fell 3.6 percent to
the lowest in more than five years. Malaysian stocks fell 5.3
percent, while the main indexes in Indonesia, Singapore and the
Philippines all lost more than 3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
