<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Hits 8-Year High Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose to an
eight-year high against the Japanese yen Tuesday as investors
continue to dump yen for safer currencies.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 147.35
Japanese yen, up from 146.15 late Monday. During the day, the
dollar reached 147.61 yen, a level not seen since August 20, 1990,
when the dollar hit 147.96 yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also rose against the German mark. The Mexican
peso fell to a record low for the second consecutive day. Canada
again intervened in foreign exchange markets, hoping to halt
further devaluation of the Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was changing hands at 1.7797 German marks, up
from 1.7759.
</P>
<P>
Investors dumped yen and Japanese stocks after a government
agency downgraded its assessment of the country's economic
prospects. Japanese stocks fell for the seventh consecutive
session, losing 1.4 percent, kindling the selloffs that reached
the Dow Jones industrial average, which dropped 112 points.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday:
1.4890 Swiss francs, down from 1.4953; 5.9690 French francs, up
from 5.9535; 1,756.00 Italian lire, up from 1,752.00; and 1.5217
Canadian dollars, up from 1.5178.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6319 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6359 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
