<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassies Closed for Security Adjustments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
temporarily closed a half-dozen embassies for security adjustments
following last week's bombings at its embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, a senior U.S. official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We're not shutting embassies down in a permanent sense. We are
not leaving. We are taking, in effect, a brief timeout in order to
make security adjustments that are necessary to be responsive to a
threat," Assistant Secretary of State Patrick Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
The bombings at U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last
Friday have killed more than 200 people, including 12 Americans,
and wounded well over 5,000.
</P>
<P>
Kennedy said the State Department and its overseas posts have
received between one dozen and two dozen threats since the embassy
bombings.
</P>
<P>
Over the course of a year, there are about 31,000 threats of
varying sorts, and all are treated seriously and checked out,
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
"We have always said to our chiefs of mission that they are
responsible to protect the lives and safety of personnel
overseas," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If the chief of mission feels that there is information
available to him or her that says, I must take a particular step,
including potentially briefly suspending operations, until
adjustments to security posture can be made, then we feel that
that is absolutely the right thing to do," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
