<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Aga Khan Foundation Ink Co-Op Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government
reached an agreement on the cooperation in economy and social
development with Aga Khan Foundation here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano and Prince Aga Khan
signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano expressed satisfaction with the agreement,
adding that it will help Mozambique achieve fast growth and bring
benefits to the Mozambican people.
</P>
<P>
Prince Aga Khan noted that the pact was oriented toward the
areas which need help most.
</P>
<P>
"We'll implement more effective and extensive projects by
providing socio-economic assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prince Aga Khan did not reveal the details of the projects and
their values.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the foundation chose to help Mozambique
because southern Africa enjoys political and currency stability
and fast economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Aga Khan Foundation, which was established in 1967, is a
complex of various institutions designed to improve the living
conditions and growth opportunities in some specific areas in the
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The foundation spends 150 million U.S. Dollars on its
assistance operations around the world each year.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda in Africa and Pakistan,
Bangladesh and Tajikistan in Asia are among the beneficiaries
from the foundation.
</P>
<P>
Prince Aga Khan arrived in Maputo Monday for a three-day visit
to Mozambique at the invitation of President Chissano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
