<HEADLINE> Damage from Nairobi Bombing to Cost $500 M: Moi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Reconstruction work in the wake
of last Friday's bomb blast will cost more than 30 billion
Shillings (500 million U.S. Dollars), Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It was a tremendous impact that has affected all sectors of
the economy," Moi said when touring the bombing site as rescuers
continued to dig through the rubble in hope of finding more
survivors after nearly 100 hours.
</P>
<P>
The explosion aimed at the U.S. embassy located in a very busy
commercial area in Nairobi has killed at least 224 people
including 12 Americans and injured nearly 5,000. Fifty-three
buildings nearby were damaged at different degrees.
</P>
<P>
Moi toured every day the bombing site, where a five-story
building collapsed completely. More bodies were feared to be
found as the survivor-searching work is coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
Moi said investigations to determine the mastermind are
underway and that Kenya was working closely with Tanzania on
several clues. He however did not confirm whether the Kenyan
police had made any arrests.
</P>
<P>
The attack was an act of terrorism which transcended
international borders, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moi also assured the international community that Kenya was
still a safe tourist destination despite the bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
An official from the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation
(FBI) said Tuesday they may issue some results from their
investigation later this week.
</P>
<P>
Both the Kenyan Criminal Investigation Department and the U.S.
FBI experts are intensifying their investigation of the bomb
raid. But it is believed that the probe will have to take months.
</P>
<P>
Several witnesses including a Kenyan guard at the U.S. embassy
have claimed that they saw a covered van, several Arab-looking
men and heard gunshots when a huge car bomb blew up.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the United States is to set up a
fund to help Kenyan victims of the Nairobi bomb blast and their
families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
