<DOCNO> XIE19980812.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Immediate Ceasefire in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Tuesday called for an immediate ceasefire in Kosovo as the
on-going fighting has had a devastating impact on the civilian
population there.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement read by August president Danilo Turk of
Slovenia, the council said the proposed ceasefire would enhance
the prospects for meaningful dialogue between the Kosovo Albanian
leadership and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia leading to a
final end to the violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It urges the concerned parties to start the negotiation as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of Kosovo can have no military solution and all
violence and acts of terrorism from whatever quarter are
unacceptable," said the 15-member council after discussing the
latest report on the matter by Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
The council also stressed the importance of the implementation
of the prohibitions imposed by the Resolution 1160 and expressed
concern over infiltration from outside of weapons and fighting
men.
</P>
<P>
The Resolution 1160 adopted by the council on March 31
prohibits U.N. members states from selling or supplying arms to
the FRY including Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, with an area of over 10,000 square km and a population
of 2 million, is a province of the Serbian Republic of the FRY.
Ethnic Albanians, making up 90 percent of the population, have
demanded independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the demand, the FRY insists that the question be
solved within the framework of the current constitution by
providing equal rights to all its inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
Annan's repot, the fourth since the conflict broke out in
February, said the situation was aggravated in July by the failure
of the FRY and the Albanian Kosovars to enter into serious
negotiations on the future status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Increased heavy fighting between the FRY security forces and
the so-called Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) raised the numbers of
civilian and military casualties to their highest point while the
displaced Kosovars have totaled 200,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
