<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Urges More Peace Efforts for Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Tuesday called for more efforts to be made to
achieve peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"Our humble experience has shown that negotiated solutions can
be found even to the conflict that the world has come to regard
as insoluble," Mandela told a banquet in honor of visiting
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"It has taught us that such solutions emerge when former
opponents reach out to find common ground," said Mandela in his
speech, text of which is available in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The South African president said that not enough was being
done to this end.
</P>
<P>
"In this testing time, the people of Palestine, and of the
Middle East as a whole, and their leaders, need all the vision
and perseverance they have demonstrated in the past in the
pursuit of comprehensive and lasting peace along the path mapped
out by the Oslo Accords," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela reaffirmed his government's support for the
Palestinians, saying his country was proud of being part of the
international consensus affirming the right of Palestine to
self-determination and statehood.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to playing our humble part, within the
limits of our resources, to help ensure that Palestine assumes
its rightful position in the global arena," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki Tuesday attacked
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's position on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
After a courtesy call on Arafat, Mbeki said it was surprising
that Netanyahu had not accepted the United States' proposals
aimed at enhancing the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to us that all that Netanyahu is doing is to try to
buy time to implement his programs, rather than work for peace
for the whole Middle East region," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived in South Africa at midnight Monday, held
talks with Mandela Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader is expected to visit Robben Island and
address a joint sitting of parliament Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
