<HEADLINE> Lesotho Official Killed by Crowd: Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A Lesotho government
official who allegedly tried to flee capital Maseru was beaten
and stoned to death Tuesday by a crowd who had blocked the road
to the border, a spokeswoman for opposition parties said.
</P>
<P>
According to witnesses, the man driving a car without number
plates bore down on the group and opened fire on them, wounding
three people, South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted
Monica Mopedi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The crowd set on the vehicle, smashing its windows, and the
unidentified man was beaten and stoned to death.
</P>
<P>
Mopedi said that a military vehicle retrieved the man's body.
The three wounded were not in a serious condition, she said.
</P>
<P>
A number plate, bearing the government's "X" code, was found
in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
Several government officials had earlier crossed the border
into South Africa, according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
There were standoffs between government and opposition
supporters in Maseru Tuesday while a crowd outside the residence
of King Letsie III was approaching 2,000 in number by Tuesday
night, Mopedi said.
</P>
<P>
A military vehicle fitted with loudspeakers was cruising the
area, exhorting the crowd to disperse.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho security force members Tuesday had to position
themselves between groupings to prevent clashes at three
locations.
</P>
<P>
Protesters gathered at the king's palace, seeking his
intervention in the row about the May election results.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) won 79 of 80
parliamentary seats in the election. But opposition parties
claimed that the election was rigged in favor of the LCD.
</P>
<P>
The protesters were not appeased by the appointment of a South
African-led committee to examine the validity of the polls,
fearing that counterfeit electoral documentation may be presented
to the committee, Mopedi said.
</P>
<P>
The committee, composed of experts from South Africa, Botswana
and Zimbabwe, would have two weeks to report its findings.
</P>
</TEXT>
